<HEADLINE> Russian FM Leaves for Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeni
Primakov flew to Washington today for a three-day official visit
to the United States, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
This trip was believed to prepare for the upcoming
Russia-U.S. summit in Helsinki scheduled for March 19-21.
</P>
<P>
Primakov's scheduled meeting with U.S. President Bill Clinton
on March 17 was put in doubt since Clinton is suffering a serious
knee tendon injury.
</P>
<P>
Clinton tore his knee tendon on the Florida estate of golfer
Greg Norman and underwent a surgery on Friday.
</P>
<P>
But Itar-Tass was assured at the White House office in
Washington that the summit meeting will not be called off.
</P>
<P>
Primakov will also meet with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright.
</P>
<P>
The main topic of these talks will be European security
problems and the START-ABM package.
</P>
<P>
Russia holds strong opposition to NATO's eastward expansion
plans, but hopes to reach a compromise at the Helsinki summit.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennadi Tarasov was quoted
as saying that during the visit Primakov plans to discuss issues
concerning strategic weapons.
</P>
<P>
They will also address such issues as cooperation in chemical
disarmament, settlement of regional crises and economic
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
