<HEADLINE> "I Saw Labe's Diaries and Photos," Says Chinese Academician </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A famous Chinese science
academician today provided new evidence that atrocities were
committed by the Japanese troops during the Nanjing Massacre about
60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
He Zehui is the wife of Qian Sanqiang, China's father of atomic
bombs. Madame He, herself a scientist in high-energy physics, told
the Chinese and Japanese press today that she had seen the diaries
of John Labe, a German who worked in Nanjing in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
Labe was then the chief representative of the German Siemens
company in China. His diaries and photos depicting Japanese
atrocities in the Nanjing Massacre were recently made public by
his granddaughter, Madame Reinhardt.
</P>
<P>
"I knew Labe," said the 83-year-old He. "I saw his diaries and
the photos he had kept."
</P>
<P>
It was around 1941 when she, as a young girl with pigtails, had
no option but to work in a Siemens lab because the Nazi government
forbade foreign scholars from leaving Germany after the start of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
After graduating from Qinghua University, she arrived in Berlin
in 1936 to study for a Ph.D. in ballistics, aware of the dire need
for technology to arm Chinese troops against Japanese invaders.
</P>
<P>
"I got to know Labe soon after I came to Siemens," she said.
"Labe was around 60 and just came back from China. He loved China
and the Chinese people."
</P>
<P>
"As I became a frequent visitor to his home, Labe showed me his
diaries and photos and told me what he saw during the massacre of
Nanjing," Madame He said.
</P>
<P>
"Labe said the Japanese were inhuman," she recalled.
</P>
<P>
She remembered that the diaries were several heavy books, and
the photos showed Chinese civilians and soldiers bein=g murdered,
buried alive or decapitated. She was shocked and outraged.
</P>
<P>
She said Madame Reinhardt was then barely 10 years old. After
the Nazi troops were overtaken by the Allied troops, and Berlin
was bombed and no longer safe, she left to work in a research
institute in south Germany and has since lost contact with the
Labe's.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the appearance of Labe's diaries and photos was
widely reported by Chinese media. Madame He didn't believe Labe
was the man she knew until she saw a picture of him on television.
</P>
<P>
"It is Labe!" she exclaimed. "Sixty years have passed, but I
recognized him as soon as I saw his picture."
</P>
<P>
Madame He, who has always avoided the media glare, today met
with reporters. "The Japanese right-wingers attempted to deny the
Nanjing Massacre, however, the history that was written in blood
cannot be erased, and Labe's diary is ironclad proof," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I regret that I don't have any photographs of me with Mr. Labe
to prove what I said," she said. "Had I had enough foresight to
see that the Japanese right-wingers would deny and distort history
in this way, I would have taken some."
</P>
<P>
Madame He left Germany for France in 1946; there, she married
Qian. She then worked at the Lab of Nuclear Chemistry of the
College of France, and the Lab of Curie.
</P>
<P>
The 83-year-old He is regarded as "China's Madam Curie" for her
discovery of ternary fission and quarto fission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
