<HEADLINE> Dhaka vows to Reduce Loadshedding in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A Bangladeshi minister today cited
the problems in gas supply as the main reason behind the present
power shortage and vowed to reduce the ever-increasing countrywide
loadshedding in April.
</P>
<P>
"The situation would begin to improve when the
Ashuganj-Bakharabad Gas Pipeline would be commissioned in April,"
Energy and Mineral Resources Minister Noor Uddin Khan told a press
conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Khan said the available electricity now can only meet 82.5
percent of the peak hour demand. To meet the shortfall, he
announced a series of short- and medium-term measures to increase
the generation of electricity.
</P>
<P>
Rehabilitation works in all power plants would be completed
next June and three barge-mounted power plants are expected to be
commissioned within the next year, adding more power to the
national grid.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the peak hour demands, The capital Dhaka city
government has announced measures to close the commercial and
shopping centers after 7 pm, impose bans on ceremonial
illumination and stagger industrial holidays to distribute the
power loads over the week.  
</P>
</TEXT>
