<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Saudi Arabia to Allow Anti-U.S. Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani today urged Saudi Arabia to lift ban on anti-U.S. and
anti-Israel rally during a Muslim pilgrimage in Mecca next month.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi authorities have warned that political activities
will not be tolerated during the Hajji.
</P>
<P>
The president was also quoted by Iran's official news agency
IRNA as saying that "At a time when the world of Islam is
suffering from division among Muslim nations, Hajji serves as a
means to help bring about unity among them."
</P>
<P>
At a recent meeting with officials in charge of Hajji
pilgrimage, Rafsanjani urged them to work hard to foster unity
among Muslim nations all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei said last week that
"expressing hatred and scorn for the disavowal of enemies of
Islam is important and necessary."
</P>
<P>
Such demonstrations have previously led to tense situations and
even bloody confrontations with the Saudi security forces. In
1987, more than 400 people were killed in clashes between Iranian
demonstrators and Saudi forces. The two countries broke off
relations from 1988 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi authorities kept a close watch on Iranian pilgrims in
past years, trying to prevent them from holding any rallies in
public.
</P>
<P>
Iran is expected to send about 70,000 pilgrims as part of a
quota set by the Saudi authorities on all Muslim countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
