<HEADLINE> OAPEC Oil Conference Opens in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A five-day bi-annual
conference of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OAPEC) on oil exploration, prosecution, refining and
petro-chemical industries opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, OAPEC Secretary-General
Abdel Aziz Al-Turki said the oil industry of the OAPEC has
realized marked progress in the fields of exploration,
industrialization, transport and marketing, overcoming many
difficulties and problems.
</P>
<P>
He told 40 oil officials and experts from various Arab
oil producing countries that the oil industry was undergoing
tremendous technological developments in exploration, prospecting,
and other fields such as refining, transport, storage and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
Al-Turki described 1996 as one of the good years in world oil
demand and price increases, saying it was necessary to follow up
market development to ensure a continued development in oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the importance of developing the capabilities
of oil workers through intensive training and exchange of
information.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait-based OAPEC, which was founded in January, 1968, is
a regional inter-governmental organization concerned with the
development of the petroleum industry through fostering
cooperation among its members. It consists of 10 Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
It has a collective total proven oil reserve of 636.2
billion barrels, amounting to 60.84 percent of the total world
oil reserve of 1045.7 billion barrels.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the 15th of its kind since the establishment of
the organization, will deal topics such as exploration,
prosecution, refining and petro-chemical industries.
</P>
<P>
The participants will also discuss matters of oil and
development in the Arab world, make analysis of the world
market, oil and energy consumption and the investment of oil
returns in joint Arab projects.
</P>
<P>
Recent studies indicated that world oil consumption last year
increased by 3 percent to record 2.1 million barrels
daily. During the next 15 years, the world oil demand is expected
to be on an average annual increase of 5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
