<HEADLINE> NEWS Analysis: A Daunting Task Facing Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government is
facing an uphill task of lifting the national economy out of the
current depression, as the debt crisis is becoming worsening.
</P>
<P>
The coming weeks and months are going to be crucial for the
government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif in financial terms. The
cost of debt servicing may eat up all or most of Pakistan's meager
foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures available here show that Pakistan's foreign debt
in the current fiscal year has exceeded an astonishing 30 billion
US dollars, an increase of almost two billion dollars over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in rupee terms, Pakistan's internal debt has risen
to 1.089 trillion rupees, equivalent to 27 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Because of the ever-increasing heavy debt service payments, the
net gains or transfer of foreign credit over the last few years
have been declining sharply, coming down from 1.36 billion dollars
in 1988-89 to a mere 388 million dollars in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, remittances from overseas Pakistanis, which once
played a significant role in bridging the gap of the balance of
payments, are shrinking fast, going down from three billion
dollars a decade ago to less than two billion dollars now.
</P>
<P>
Debt servicing is the single largest item of expenditure in the
federal budget. In 1995-96 it amounted to 193.1 billion rupees
(about 4.9 billion dollars), accounting for more than half of the
total revenue, almost 38 percent of total expenditure and 46.3
percent of current expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Persistent current account and fiscal deficits which are
financed by domestic borrowing have eventually led to a high
debt-GDP ratio of 89 percent.
</P>
<P>
The consequences of this persistent borrowing are that every
citizen of Pakistan is now indebted to the tune of 17,000 rupees
(424 dollars) while the per capita income in Pakistan is only
14,927 rupees (372 dollars) at present.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, who assumed his premiership on February 17, has mounted
a massive and innovative effort to unburden the nation of the huge
debt portfolio by asking the people both at home and abroad to
contribute generously towards the specially created accounts for
this purpose.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, who came to power after sitting three years on the
opposition bench, has identified the debt as public enemy number
one of Pakistan and has urged the nation to contribute to his Debt
Retirement Fund.
</P>
<P>
While It is encouraging that the government is giving top
priority to the debt problem, there is still some doubt as to
whether Sharif's call would generate enough money to repay all or
a substantial part of the mounting debt for which the present
government is equally responsible.
</P>
<P>
The people's initial response to the Fund is encouraging,
although exact figures are not available yet.
</P>
<P>
However, given the hefty amount of debt burden, the role of
these contributions will be only marginal, not to mention the
short-term high interests the government has to pay.
</P>
<P>
With 1.2 billion dollars due to be paid this month, the
government is left with no choice but to borrow at least one
billion dollar in short-term loans.
</P>
<P>
One of the main causes of the rising foreign debt is the trade
deficit which stood at 3.5 billion dollars in the last fiscal
year. The primary source of meeting the debt is foreign investment
which remains at around one billion dollars, much lower than
needed.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit is blamed for the debt. In the last fiscal
year, the government had planned to borrow only 42 billion rupees
(1.04 billion dollars) from domestic market to meet the budget
deficit, but the sum has already crossed the 100 billion rupee
mark and may reach 150 billion rupees (3.75 billion dollars) in
the next few months.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believe that to improve the trade deficit
situation, the only option is to increase exports by enhancing the
competitiveness of Pakistani goods in the international market.
Pakistan, however, has a very long way to go in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The present government is now taking all possible measures to
revitalize the economy. Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz has said the
revival of the industrial sector and speedy growth in agriculture
and manufacturing on a large scale are the top priority of the new
government.
</P>
<P>
"Productivity and Production" can ensure high growth rate,
larger exports and more jobs, thus yielding more revenues to
gradually lessen the budget deficit and foreign debt, said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Most economists here agree that increased production and
productivity can solve the problems in the long term. But the
question is that Pakistan's economic position seems too fragile to
stand that long.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, heavy cuts in non-development expenditure may be the
only way to lay a solid foundation for the country's long-term
goal.
</P>
<P>
As the defense budget of 133 billion rupees (3.32 billion
dollars) -- the second biggest drag on resources -- may not be
curtailed, the choices of the new government are limited.
</P>
<P>
Much would depend on whether the new government will be in a
position to take tough decisions instead of resorting only to
stopgap measures, the analysts said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
