<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Divided on Calls for Albania Military Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
APELDOORN, Netherlands, March 15 (Xinhua) -- European Union
foreign ministers, convening an informal meeting in the Dutch town
of Apeldoorn, were divided on Saturday on whether to back calls
for military intervention in the chaotic Albania.
</P>
<P>
Danish Foreign Minister Niels Helveg Petersem, whose country
holds the OSCE presidency, said his country was infavour of having
the international community put together a force.
</P>
<P>
According to Dutch EU presidency sources, Danmark's position
was supported by Spain and Austria.
</P>
<P>
But British Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifking told reporters as
he arrived for the meeting it was "premature" to think about such
a move, a stance which was shared by his German colleague Klaus
Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
Sweden's Lena Hjelm-Wallen was blunt about the EU's
predicament. "Frankly, we don't know what to do," she told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Dutch Foreign Minister Hans van Mierlo, hosting the Apeldoorn
meeting, said the EU was not ruling anything out and that his
colleagues would be considering a number of options.
</P>
<P>
OSCE(Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe)
mediator Franz Vranitzky said on Friday there was no alternative
to foreign intervention to halt Albania's descent into chaos.
</P>
<P>
Despite having to discuss Albania, the EU ministers were keen
to get the issue behind them so they could address on Sunday some
long-term EU issues on the planned agenda, such as enlargement and
the relationship with NATO enlargement plans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
