<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Censured for Barring Canadian Employees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States has hit "an
all-time low" by banning employees of a Canadian company from the
entering the U.S., said Canadian International Trade Minister Art
Eggleton.
</P>
<P>
Four directors of Toronto-based Sherritt International Corp.
were notified Friday that they would be barred, along with their
spouses and children, from entering the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"I think it reaches an all-time low though. They are getting
down to the employee ranks," Eggleton was quoted as saying by
reports today.
</P>
<P>
"I think that's a sorry situation and I think it continues to
be a violation of international trade rules," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last July, the U.S. issued similar letters to seven Sherritt
executives on grounds that they were violating the Helms-Burton
law, which seeks to punish companies doing business in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Sherritt operates a nickle company in Cuba and is expanding
into other sectors in the Caribbean island country.
</P>
<P>
Eggleton said that Canada will join the European Union (EU)
case at the World Trade Organization and provide testimony about
the "chilling effect" of Helms-Burton on trade with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Canada may take its own complaint against Helms-Burton to a
North American Free Trade Agreement panel depending upon the
progress of the EU case, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. has no business trying to foist its laws on other
countries. If it wants to deal with Cuba, it should deal with Cuba
directly and not try to punish companies in Canada and other
countries through its law," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
