<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Bankruptcies Up 20 Percent in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Business and personal bankruptcies
in Canada soared to a record in 1996, up 20 percent than in 1995,
the previous record year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from Industry Canada show 79,631 consumers and
14,229 businesses went bankrupt across Canada in 1996, up 23
percent and 7.5 percent respectively over 1995.
</P>
<P>
A sluggish economy and consumers' easy access to credit are
being blamed here for the rapid bankruptcy increases.
</P>
<P>
To Aron Gampel, Bank of Nova Scotia economist, Canada's
plodding economic recovery is the root of cause of the
bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
"Slow growth in the economy is not conducive to lowering the
bankruptcy rate," Aron Gampel was quoted as saying by reports
today.
</P>
<P>
"The bankruptcy numbers have tended to rise over the past 12 to
24 months because of the sluggishness in the Canadian economy," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The rise in consumer failures is in part due to the spread of
credit-card use, according to Sherry Cooper, chief economist at
investment dealer Nesbitt Burns.
</P>
<P>
"Banks have blanketed low-income areas with credit cards and
people over-extended themselves," she said, adding "credit is
readily available and that kind of credit is extremely expensive."
</P>
<P>
Latest figures show that Canadians had outstanding credit-card
balances in October 1996 of 13.7 billion U.S. dollars, up from
12.8 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
People may not see much improvement in the country's overall
bankruptcy picture over the next few years even if the economy
grows at a healthy rate, analysts here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
