<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 15 (Xinhua)-- This year's first 400 Somali
pilgrims have left their country for Saudi Arabia by air in
the past two days.
</P>
<P>
The pilgrims are from Mogadishu, Bossaso, Berbera and
Hargeisa.
</P>
<P>
Amir Lsse Aidid, the Chairman of Africa Airlines, said his
airlines has planned 10 flights to Jeddah for transporting
1,500 pilgrims this year.
</P>
<P>
The pilgrims are required to take 820 U.S. Dollars with them
to buy non-refundable two-way tickets to Saudi Arabia and for
other use there.
</P>
<P>
Only pilgrims holding cholera and yellow fever vaccinations
certificates can be allowed to fly to Jeddah.
</P>
<P>
The three local air agencies -- Africa, Dallo and Kilimanjaro
Air -- are expected to transport more than 7,500 Somali pilgrims
to Saudi Arabia this year.
</P>
<P>
Air agencies from Kenya and Djibouti, both bordering on
Somalia, provide visa facilitation for pilgrims, resulting in the
increase of pilgrims this year.
</P>
<P>
The flights to Jeddah will stop by early next month, according
to instructions by Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The Hadj will take place after more than 30 days in the holy
town of Mecca.
</P>
<P>
The pilgrims will be provided with Somalia's blue flags with
the white star at the center, so that they can find each other
more easier in Mecca. enditem



