<HEADLINE> AL Leader Condemns Shooting Incident Near </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Maguid,
secretary general of the League of Arab States, today condemned
the killing of seven Israeli schoolgirls by a Jordanian soldier,
and described it an "obstacle" to the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said that he regretted for the occurrence of this incident
"no matter whether it was targeted at Arabs or non-Arabs."
</P>
<P>
The Arab League's secretary general denounced this kind of
operations which "obstruct the peace process in the region which,
anyway, has actually been obstructed."
</P>
<P>
He believed that the peace process would "still be suspended
by this kind of things."
</P>
<P>
Six other children were also wounded when the Jordanian
soldier fired an automatic rifle at an Israeli bus running along
the Jordan River Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Maguid left Beirut this evening for Cairo, winding up a
three-day visit to Lebanon during which he held meetings with the
Lebanese leaders and took part in activities marking the 19th
anniversary of the Israeli occupation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at the Beirut International Airport, the
secretary general reiterated his support for Lebanon, noting that
the Israeli occupation in south Lebanon must be terminated and
the resistance was an "honor of the Arab nation."
</P>
<P>
Rallies and other activities were held in Lebanon Thursday
and Friday to mark the first Israeli invasion into Lebanon on
March 14, 1978, which constituted the start of Israel's
occupation of some one tenth of Lebanon's territories. 
</P>
