<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan is the largest per capita recipient of
Japanese aid in the world, Jordan's news agency Petra
today quoted Japanese ambassador Takayuki Kimura as saying.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, Jordan received 40 percent of the net
aid inflow into the Middle East from Japan, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is also the biggest recipient of the non-project grant
from Japan among the Middle East countries, Kimura said, adding
that Jordan is accepting other kind of aid, such as project
grants, project loans and technical assistance from Japan.
</P>
<P>
He said Japan appreciates and supports Jordan's policies toward
the Middle East peace and its efforts toward self-sustainable
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Karim Kabariti
signed the latest agreement to accept some 21 million U.S. dollars
grant from Japan.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Union Bank of Switzerland (UBS), one of the world
top banks, showed confidence in Jordan's economy by identifying
eight Jordanian companies as potential firms for foreign
investments, Jordan's news agency Petra reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The UBS will hold a conference in London on May 15 in an effort
to promote the eight companies among 60 of UBS clients.
</P>
<P>
The eight state-holding companies, in which the government
holds large stakes, are from the industries of phosphate, potash,
cement, electricity and telecommunications as well as the bank and
investment sector, said Amman Financial Market (AFM) Director
General Wahib Shair.
</P>
<P>
A UBS delegation arrived in Amman last Wednesday for a two-day
visit to prepare for the conference, said Shair, adding that the
delegation also met with several Jordanian ministers and officials.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in 1993, Jordan missed many investment
opportunities as foreign investors were required to obtain a prior
approval for investment from the Prime Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"But, with changes in the law brought about by the (Cairo)
Middle East and North Africa economic summit (last November), the
need for prior approval from the Prime Ministry was canceled," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Shair stressed the importance of reversing "the traditional
way" of attracting foreign investments, to a new approach
of "meeting investors, showing them we are interested, listening
to their views and communicating their ideas to the government."
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait will impose a 100 percent custom tariffs
on tobacco and cigarettes from July 1, 1997, Director General of
the Public Administration for Customs Abdallah Al-Ghanim said
today.
</P>
<P>
He made the announcement at a press conference during a
seminar on coordinated tariff systems among Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states being currently held in Kuwait within the
framework of cooperation between the GCC countries and the
European commission.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait currently imposes 50 percent of custom tariffs on
imported cigarettes and it is a major consumer country of
cigarettes in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ghanim also said the GCC states, including Saudi Arabia,
Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Oman and Bahrain, would
soon unify the customs tariffs on some items.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- A five-day bi-annual conference of the
Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) on oil
exploration, prosecution, refining and petro-chemical industries
opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony, OAPEC Secretary-General
Abdel Aziz Al-Turki said the oil industry of the OAPEC has
realized marked progress in the fields of exploration,
industrialization, transport and marketing, overcoming many
difficulties and problems.
</P>
<P>
He told 40 oil officials and experts from various Arab
oil producing countries that the oil industry was undergoing
tremendous technological developments in exploration, prospecting,
and other fields such as refining, transport, storage and
marketing.
</P>
<P>
The OAPEC has a collective total proven oil reserve of 636.2
billion barrels, amounting to 60.84 percent of the total world
oil reserve of 1045.7 billion barrels.
</P>
<P>
Recent studies indicated that world oil consumption last year
increased by 3 percent to record 2.1 million barrels daily. During
the next 15 years, the world oil demand is expected to be on an
average annual increase of 5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
