<P>
The king, cutting short his visit to Spain and coming back to
Amman Thursday, has expressed condolence to Israeli Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu through a telephone call.
</P>
<P>
A Jordanian soldier Thursday opened fire at a group of Israeli
school girls who were on school outing in the Naharayim area on
the Jordanian side of the border, killing seven girls and
wounding six others.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old murderer, Ahmad Mousa Dakamseh, has been
arrested.
</P>
<P>
The king, who is scheduled to visit Washington on March 18,
has rescheduled his visit there.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan said Friday that the attack was
an isolated incident and did not reflect Jordan's policy or
conduct of its armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The attack happened when the Israeli government pushes on its
Jewish settlement policy in Arab's East Jerusalem despite
international opposition and Jordan's efforts to prevent Israel
from doing so become futile over and over again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
