<HEADLINE> Arafat: Gaza Meeting Aims to Save Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat told foreign diplomats today that "I called this meeting
for one purpose, that is, to save the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Addressing an international conference at the Shawa Center in
Gaza, Arafat called for international help to extricate the
regional peace process from a deep crisis stemming from the
Israeli government decision to build a new Jewish settlement in
the Arab East Jerusalem, according to a report of JMCC, a
Palestinian press service based in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The participants included Egyptian Deputy Foreign Minister
Bader Hamam, Jordanian Ambassador to the Arab League Nayef
Al-Qadi, Norwegian Ambassador Muna Yol as well as diplomats of the
United States, Russia, Japan, the European Union and the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is very dangerous," Arafat said. "The settlement
activities in Jerusalem and its surrounding areas ... and other
parts of the Palestinian territories ... constitute a plan
targeting to destroy the peace process."
</P>
<P>
Arafat noted that settlement activities and land confiscation
are continuing on an unprecedented scale not only in East
Jerusalem but in Hebron and even in the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
"We strive to protect the peace process ... but the signed
agreements should be respected," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader called for a collective responsibility
to find a mechanism to confront (Israeli) non-commitment to the
signed agreements. He added that "non-commitment means that we
have been left without a partner in the peace process. We need
your assistance in bringing about an honest implementation (of
the agreements) and finding a mechanism to guarantee that
unilateral decisions are not taken."
</P>
<P>
"I call on you to work together in this conference in order to
protect the peace process from harms caused by building
settlement, creating facts on the ground, showing arrogance and
dictating decisions," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat declared: "We would like to reaffirm our total
commitment to the peace process and the signed agreements. At the
same time I call upon the Israeli government to be a true partner
and not to take unilateral decisions that threaten the peace
process."
</P>
<P>
"Peace and settlement do not meet. Terrorism, settlement, land
confiscation, acts of imposing facts on the ground should all be
the language of the past as the language of the future is
security, stability and justice," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I call on the Israeli government to retract its settlement
decisions to give the the peace process the opportunity it
deserves," stated Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Arafat took the opportunity to reiterate the ultimate
Palestinian goal to establish an independent Palestinian state
with Jerusalem as its capital, alongside the state of
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
