<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Inject More Resources into Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has planned to
inject more resources into tourism to attract more tourists,
Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa said today.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when opening the 52-room Serena Inn owned
by the Aga Khan, the Shia Ismaili spiritual leader, at the heart
of Stone Town in Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said the government, with the help of donors, will
strive to inject more resources into tourism supportive services,
infrastructure and advertising.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to do so in the belief that even as the tourism
sector is usually a private sector affairs, to succeed it
requires public sector support on infrastructure, including good
airports, transport and communication networks," he said.
</P>
<P>
He told the Aga Khan that Tanzania is reviewing the tax
profile of the industry so as to make the country a "truly
competitive destination for private investment, especially
foreign direct investment".
</P>
<P>
As many as 39 million US Dollars of investment follows the
opening of three other tourist lodges in the northern tourist
circuit and a luxury tented camp in the Tanzania Mainland.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa commended the Aga Khan for his keen interest in
developing the tourism sector in the eastern African country,
adding that his investment in the field has promoted quality
tourism.
</P>
<P>
He told the Aga Khan that tourism is the largest foreign
exchange earner for Tanzania and provides about 30,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists has remarkably increased in Tanzania,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The number has jumped from 64,000 in 1984 to 326,194 last year
and revenues from the sector have shot up from 9.4 million Dollars
in 1984 to 322 million Dollars last year," said.
</P>
<P>
"Our target, which we consider quite achievable, is to receive
500,000 tourists by the year 2000, earn 585 million Dollars a
year and create 45,000 jobs," the president said.
</P>
<P>
He told the Aga Khan that with partners like Serena Inn, with the
wide array of tourist attractions and with correct government
policies, Tanzania could certainly be competitive.
</P>
<P>
The Aga Khan arrived in the country on Thursday for an
official visit. enditem

