<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Jews Ask for Transparency over Pre-war </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- France's major Jewish group, the
Representative Council of Jews of France (CRIF), today called on
the government and the Bank of France to give transparency to an
estimated 1 billion franc (200 million U.S. dollar) pre-war bank
deposits of French Jews who died in Nazi death camps.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the daily Le Monde published today,
the Bank of France has lost trail of the individual accounts of
Jews who were deported to Nazi death camps by the Vichy
collaboration regime during World War II.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the value of these accounts, which were in
default of heirs, could amount to more than 1 billion francs in
its present value, in accordance with a study made in 1951 by a
government group on the archives of Vichy police department in
charge of Jewish questions.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for French banks to be accused of hiding
Jewish accounts which were not claimed because of the Nazi
Holocaust during the war, although the Paris municipality was
accused last year of maintaining Jewish real estate properties
confiscated by the Vichy regime.
</P>
<P>
"The French banks have neither tried in their whole to make
known the reality of these accounts, nor attempted to find their
heirs, and have not made the least gesture to help the Jewish
orphans whose parents were exterminated (by Nazis)," said CRIF.
</P>
<P>
The CRIF also asked for the revelation of the whereabouts of
the deposits of Jewish families whose members were all killed, as
well as the life insurance contracts signed between these Jews and
French banks.
</P>
<P>
It said that "all the necessary investigations should be made
by the working group" to be set up within two weeks by the French
government on Jewish properties robbed by Nazis and the Vichy
regime.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Alain Juppe announced in January that he
would set up a working group to investigate the whereabouts of
Jewish properties lost during the war.
</P>
<P>
The French laws require the banks to submit to the state all
accounts which are not claimed 30 years after they are deposited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
