<HEADLINE> UK Jobless Total at 4 Million, Labor Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The real number of people out of
work in Britain stood at more than four million, said the main
opposition Labor Party's employment spokesman Peter Hain Friday.
</P>
<P>
Using the most recent official Labor Force Survey, Hain said
that 4,401,000 people were looking for work at the end of last
summer, more than double the official count then of 2,043,000.
</P>
<P>
Labor's figures, which were based on the government's claimant
count plus the number of people looking for work but unable to
claim the Job Seeker's Allowance and those on compulsory
government schemes, are in line with estimates made by the Trade
Union Congress and the independent Unemployment Unit (UU).
</P>
<P>
The UU put the current underlying unemployment rate at 17
percent compared to the official rate of 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hain said that the fall in the official dole figures is
increasingly accounted for by the gap between those allowed to
claim unemployment benefit and those actually unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the UU estimated that more than half of the drop in
the claimant count since last October, 137,000 out of 255,000, had
been due to the Jobseeker's Allowance which tightens benefit
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
Hain said that a Labor government would conduct a review to
introduce a "politically impartial measure" of unemployment.
</P>
</TEXT>
