<HEADLINE> Liberia's Kromah Pardoned by Peacekeepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping
force known as ECOMOG has pardoned Liberia's presidential
candidate and ex-warlord Alhaji Kromah found of hiding a large
quantity of arms in his home, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The report said this was announced by ECOMOG Commander
Major-General Victor Malu in Monrovia on Friday, a few hours
after Kromah tendered his unreserved apology.
</P>
<P>
The peacekeeping force has earlier in two separate raids found
a large quantity of arms in Kromah's home in Liberia's capital
Monrovia and in his country home some 260 kilometers north of the
capital.
</P>
<P>
He was first put under house arrest by the ECOMOG and then
transferred to the local police. An earlier report said he was
expected to be prosecuted this week.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG has required the Liberian interim authorities to
drop the charges being prepared against Kromah, the leader of the
United Liberation Movement of Liberia -- one of the key warring
factions during the seven-year Liberian civil war.
</P>
<P>
Malu said the ECOMOG's clemency was "dictated purely by our
desire to ensure that the peace process remains on course".
</P>
<P>
It is a recognition of the fact that "Kromah is a key player
in present day Liberia," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was also taken into consideration that Kromah voluntarily
started disarmament of his faction in Voinjama in September 1996,
two months ahead of the concerned official commencement, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG high command also made a request for the release of
all those so far found with arms and already handed over to the
Liberian authorities for prosecution, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Malu, however, warned that the plea by the ECOMOG "should not
be construed as license" for those still in possession of arms.
</P>
<P>
The ECOMOG would not relent in its efforts to rid Liberia out
of arms, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Kromah said in his apology issued at a press conference in his
home that "I wish to admit to my error for having arms at my
premises after the January 31, 1997, the deadline for disarmament,"
according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Kromah was quoted as saying he has "no motive, no desire, no plan"
to engage himself in any activity to undermine or disrupt the
peace process, security and current happiness of Liberians.
</P>
</TEXT>
