<HEADLINE> No German Troops Sent to Albania: Kinkel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
APELDOORN, Netherlands, March 15 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign
Minister Klaus Kinkel on Saturday ruled out any option of his
country sending troops to Albania, warning against hasty military
intervention.
</P>
<P>
"German soldiers will not go into Albania," Kinkel told
reporters, using the strongest language yet to underline his
country's position.
</P>
<P>
"We can't get involved in another adventure," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel, who was meeting his EU colleagues at an informal
meeting in the Dutch town of Apeldoorn, said that the EU was ready
to offer humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
"But the Albanians had to put down their weapons and clear
entry into their ports," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel also refused to join the growing chorus calling for
Albanian President Sali Berisha to step down.
</P>
<P>
"If there is to be a political solution, the president will
have to consider when and how he can contribute to a solution," he
said. 
