<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's New Criminal Law Expected To Improve Securities Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese financial experts and
officials today praised the country's new criminal law, and said
that the inclusion of crimes in the securities business, the first
time for China to do so, will help make for a healthier securities
market.
</P>
<P>
"The new clauses on securities crimes will help prevent crime
and will provide powerful legal support for the healthy and steady
development of the securities market in China," Wang Guogang,
deputy director of the financial research center of the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences, told Xinhua by phone. "The market
impact of the new clauses will be far-reaching," he said.
</P>
<P>
The amended Criminal Law was approved on Friday by the National
People's Congress, China's legislature. Sentences for those who
violate securities rules by providing inside information,
spreading false information, or manipulating securities prices can
be up to ten years in prison.
</P>
<P>
The new law, which takes effect October 1, will provide the
authorities with a more powerful and effective legal tool to deal
with violations, Wang said, pointing out that "The amendments to
the law reflect the hard facts of some fairly serious violations
of securities market rules."
</P>
<P>
After more than five years of development, China's securities
market is well on its way toward accelerated expansion. The stock
market has 564 companies listed, compared with 530 at the end of
last year, with total share value exceeding 129.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has maintained a policy of securities
market standardization and has done everything possible to
establish a legal framework for the market, an official with the
China Securities Regulatory Commission, the industry watchdog,
noted, "But the existing market regulations have proven inadequate
for an accelerated market expansion."
</P>
<P>
He explained that market irregularities have increased
securities investment risks, damaged investor confidence, and even
posed a threat to the long-term development of the securities
market.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Bingxun, director of the market development department of
the China Securities Executive Council, pointed out that harsh
legal penalties are necessary to curb securities-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
"Crimes in the securities industry usually involve a huge
amount of money, so for the benefit of a healthy and orderly
securities market we need a strong legal weapon to deal with
them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang Guogang noted that a market economy is one governed by the
law and by market rules, and that the securities market, as a part
of it, can develop healthily only when there is a sound legal
framework to build on.
</P>
<P>
"When one takes the long view and looks at it against a broader
economic backdrop, improving the legal basis of the securities
market becomes even more significant," Wang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
