<HEADLINE> Record Sales at Tianjin Export Commodities Trade Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Eighth Export Commodities
Trade Fair in this north China's largest port city ended Saturday,
with a record number of contracts signed, worth a total of 650
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented an increase of 6.57 percent from the
previous trade fair, according to local officials.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin's first fair of this kind was in 1990. According to
Wang Shuzu, deputy director of the organizing committee, nearly
2,000 businesses took part in this year's fair, which was
sponsored by 13 provinces, autonomous regions, and municipalities,
and by other organizations. It is one of six national export
commodities fairs approved by the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Relatively heavily-traded commodities like textiles, clothing,
grains, food, hardware, ore products, petrochemicals,
pharmaceuticals, machinery, auto parts, animal husbandry products,
carpets, handicrafts, and various kinds of light industrial
products were featured.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume with the United States was 137 million US dollars,
ranking first among the participating countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The next trade fair is scheduled for March 8-15 next year.
</P>
