<HEADLINE> Chinese Woman Sets Race Record at HK Golden Mile Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- China's Zhang Jinqing set a new
race record of four minutes 37 seconds to win the women's event at
the annual Hong Kong International Golden Mile Race Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The winning time of 20-year-old Zhang from North China's Hebei
Province beat the six-year-old race record of 4:41 held by British
Karen Hutcheson.
</P>
<P>
Britain's defending champion Shirley Griffiths led most of the
race but was overtaken by Zhang some 200 meters from the finish
line. Griffiths was timed two hundredths of a second slower than
the Chinese winner.
</P>
<P>
Liu Haiyan, 22, from South China's Guangdong Province finished
third in 4:46 and her teammate Zeng Yuying, 23, was fifth in
4:51. This was Zeng's fourth appearance in the race, having
finished runner-up last year and in 1994 and third in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"I'm happy to beat the record," said a smiling Zhang after the
awarding ceremony. "The course is nice and the weather was good
today, not so warm as I had expected."
</P>
<P>
Zhang said she just ran as she had planned -- following the
leader for most of the distance and overtaking the lead in the
later stage.
</P>
<P>
"Although we two were evenly matched, I knew things were
determined when I overtook her (Griffiths)," she said.
</P>
<P>
"I did what I could. But Zhang really ran faster than I could
today. What else can I say? " said a disappointed Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
But she said she would try to compete here again next
year. That would be her fourth time here for the 24-year-old from
Newcastle.
</P>
<P>
John Henwood from New Zealand won the men's title in 4:08.
</P>
<P>
Henwood, with a personal best time for mile of 3:59, edged
Chinese Hou Gang by one hundredth of a second. But the New
Zealander failed to beat the race mark of 4:05, held since 1995 by
Briton Anthony Whiteman.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Darren Spawforth finished third in 4:11 and another
Chinese Zhu Yueqiang was seventh in 4:28.
</P>
<P>
"It's really a good win, with so many spectators cheering on
for you," said Henwood after his win.
</P>
<P>
"It's a bit windy today. But the weather is good, not so hot
as back in New Zealand, and the course is good," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
