<HEADLINE> North China Port City To Develop New Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A total of 60 infrastructure
projects estimated to cost 3.2 billion yuan are scheduled to be
built this year in the Binhai New Area of Tianjin, which includes
the Tianjin Development Zone, Tianjin Free Trade Zone, and a
harbor area.
</P>
<P>
This is north China's largest port city. Construction work on
the new area began three years ago as part of its 21st century
development strategy. So far, more than six billion yuan have been
spent on more than 120 infrastructure projects in the area.
</P>
<P>
The large expenditure is to be used for highways, power
stations, expansion of Binhai airport, and a sewage and drainage
project, and is expected to help the area increase the amount of
overseas funds by improving its investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale industries have also been set up in the new area,
covering the fields of electronics, foodstuff, metallurgy, and
petrochemicals.
</P>
<P>
The area now has a group of enterprises each with more than 100
million or one billion US dollars invested. The area added more
than 600 foreign-funded enterprises last year, with contracted
overseas funds of more than 1.87 billion dollars. Investors from
other parts of China have also been providing funds for the area.
</P>
<P>
The area generated more than 32 billion yuan in GDP last year,
a 28.3 percent rise from the previous year, and nearly double the
growth rate for the entire city. The area contributes nearly 30
percent of the city's economic growth now.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin's goal this year is to pull in 2.3 billion dollars of
overseas investment, which will mean a 15 percent increase over
1996. In order to increase the use of overseas investment, the
city will try to get local companies to be listed abroad on stock
exchanges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
