<HEADLINE> Kinkel Says Germany Has Taken in Enough Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- In anticipation of a refugee exodus
from Albania, German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel has said that
his country has taken in too many foreign refugees and can accept
no further major inflows.
</P>
<P>
"Under current circumstances we can no longer take in any
significant number of refugees. Our boat is full," Kinkel was
quoted today by the German Sunday newspaper Welt am Sonntag as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel noted that Germany, in comparison to other European
countries, has accepted much more refugees.
</P>
<P>
Some 320,000 refugees from Bosnia and 120,000 asylum-seekers,
overwhelmingly ethnic Albanians from the Yugoslavian autonomous
province of Kosovo, are currently living in Germany.
</P>
<P>
But the German foreign minister also asserted that Germany does
not want to be "inhumane" and does not reject in principle the
acceptance of refugees.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Albanians have fled the civil unrest sweeping
across the Balkan country since January after pyramid investment
schemes collapsed, costing the life savings of many Albanians.
</P>
</TEXT>
