<HEADLINE> Defending Champion Wanda Wins Opener of 1997 Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Dalian Wanda
took a steady step toward its third title in four years Sunday by
beating Vanguard Huandao 2-0 in the first match of the 1997 season
of Chinese soccer first-division league Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Wanda, which won the league in 1994 and 1996, extended its
unbeaten record to 35 matches after the Sunday's victory.
</P>
<P>
Wanda went ahead in the 34th minute when Wang Peng found the
net with a lob, which flew straight into the goal over the keeper
of Huandao.
</P>
<P>
Xu Hui made it 2-0 in the 54th minute in a quick counter-attack.
</P>
<P>
Huandao, who was promoted from the second division after taking
the top place last season, almost scored for several times but
failed to convert the chances into goals.
</P>
<P>
Under the coach of German Klaus Schlappner, former head coach
of the Chinese national squad, Huandao moved from Wuhan of Hubei
Province to the soccer-crazy city, which was just appoved by the
National People's Congress as the China's fourth municipality
after Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
But it was hard for Huandao to live up to the high expectations
by a boisterous crowd of 40,000 before a much stronger Wanda.
</P>
<P>
Schlappner, who earned a name of aggressiveness during his
coaching of the Chinese national team, admitted the result
reflected a gap between the two champions from the first and
second divisions.
</P>
<P>
Last season's runner-up Shanghai Shenhua proved too strong for
the visiting Yanbian Aodong when Shenhua scored a 2-0 win at home.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jun opened the scoring in the third minute after heading
home a cross from Fan Zhiyi, China's footballer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Fan scored a penalty goal in the 57th minute after Aodong
committed a foul in the box, anchoring the win for Shenhua, who
won the league title in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In Guangzhou, Guangdong Province, Guangzhou Apollo edged
Guangdong Hongyuan 1-0 in a rain-soaked match.
</P>
<P>
Tan Ende scored the sole goal for Apollo only five minutes into
action on a scramble in the box.
</P>
<P>
In the day's other matches, Chinese Soccer Association Cup
title-holder Beijing Guo'an was forced to a goalless draw by
Sichuan Quanxing, August First ousted Tianjin Lifei 1-0, and Jinan
Taishan suffered a surprise 0-1 loss to Qingdao Hainiu, the other
team promoted from the second division. 
</P>
</TEXT>
