<HEADLINE> IMF Praises Egypt's Economic Reform Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has expressed deep satisfaction with results achieved by the
economic reform program being implemented by the Egyptian
government, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Arvind Subramanian, IMF resident representative here, expected
that the volume of the foreign capital flow into Egypt this year
would reach 1.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
He anticipated that the rate of annual economic growth in Egypt
would rise to 5 percent by the end of 1997 from 4 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The IMF official said Egypt has the potential to raise the
growth rate to 7 or 8 percent for raising standards of living and
reducing unemployment rates in a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate has dropped to 5.7 percent at the end of
January, while the budget deficit has dropped to 0.8 percent of
the Gross National Product(GNP), he said, describing this
percentage as very good with regard to economies of developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
According to previous IMF reports, inflation stood at 7 percent
while the budget deficit accounted for 1.5 percent of GNP last
December.
</P>
<P>
The IMF representative denied reports on differences between
the Egyptian government and the IMF as regards stepping up the
tempo of the country's privatization process.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt steadily proceeds in the privatization process according
to the program agreed upon with the Fund taking into consideration
social impact of the program," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of keeping the momentum of the
structural adjustment program specially in the coming period for
implementing further reforms in monetary and financial domain.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that permanent coordination and
consultation between the government and the Fund should continue
in order to implement the reform program without any side
effects.
</P>
<P>
The government pledged to expand privatization, further
liberalize foreign trade and reform financial system under
an agreement with the IMF on starting the second stage of the
Egyptian economic reform program in July 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
