<HEADLINE> Rapid Growth in Shanghai's Foreign Trade (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
economic center, reported a record 22.26 billion US dollars worth
of foreign trade last year, up 16.8 percent from that of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that Shanghai's exports increased 14.3
percent to 13.24 billion dollars worth in 1996. The growth in
foreign trade exceeded that for the city's GDP, which was 13
percent last year. Foreign trade accounted for 4.6 percent of the
GDP, up 1.3 percentage points from 1995.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that foreign trade will occupy an increasingly
important position in the city's economy, and that its development
will depend more and more on foreign trade in the future.
</P>
<P>
The city's import also reported a steady rise. According to
statistics, 943 million dollars worth of equipment was imported,
116 million dollars worth of timber, and 288 million dollars worth
of electrical household appliances last year, up 31.9 percent,
72.9 percent and 1,200 percent, respectively, from 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The more widely Shanghai opens to the outside, the more trade
partners and markets it has," said one analyst.
</P>
<P>
The city has had remarkable success in market expansion in
neighboring countries, and in Eastern Europe and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
It has established trade relations with 199 countries and
regions across the world, 16 more than in 1995, and the number of
trade partners that do more than five million dollars in trade
with the city climbed to 81 in 1996 from the previous year's 75.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rapid Growth in Shanghai's Foreign Trade (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The city's foreign-funded enterprises have also seen a rapid
increase in exports. The city approved 2,106 overseas investment
projects last year. The overall number of such projects is 15,692,
giving a great push to foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
These firms brought in 4 billion dollars from exports last
year, up 51.4 percent from 1995, and accounting for 30.3 percent
of the city's total export volume.
</P>
<P>
"The municipality has paid great attention to promoting exports
of its major products," said a municipal government official. It
has 60 products whose export volume exceeded 50 million dollars
each. Of these, 20 were worth more than 100 million dollars each.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the city's export structure is
improving, with exports of mechanical and electrical products
reaching 3.3 billion dollars in 1996, up 24.8 percent from the
previous year. The growth rate was the largest for the past few
years, analysts say, adding that exports of software technology
have also been growing.
</P>
<P>
"The city has attracted many foreign trade projects from
provinces along the Yangtze River Delta, along the coast and in
the country's central and western parts," the official
noted. Figures show that trade through Shanghai port was worth
more than 52 billion dollars last year, a record for the Chinese
ports.
</P>
<P>
The city's exports for the first two months of this year were
up more than 10 percent from the same period of last year,
according to the lastest official statistics. Although these signs
are encouraging, say some analysts, the city's foreign trade
situation is still somewhat unfavorable. Technology-intensive
products do not have a broad overseas market, for example,
export-tax refund rates have fallen, and protectionism in overseas
market is becoming increasingly serious.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government is hoping to maintain a growth rate in
foreign trade of 10 percent this year, an official says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
