<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Demands NATO-Russia Accord Be of Binding Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
demanded that any agreement signed between NATO and Russia should
be legally binding, a Finnish newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Finnish newspaper of Helsinki Sanomat,
Yeltsin said that NATO should make a clear commitment to guarantee
Russia's national security.
</P>
<P>
"The NATO expansion, if it becomes true, will radically reduce
our geo-political and geo-strategic position," Yeltsin said,
adding that this will oblige Russia to take "necessary"
countermeasures.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that the alliance's move to expand into Central
and Eastern European countries will reduce mutual trust between
Russia and Western countries and may create new confrontation.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, NATO declared in a statement that it will not
permanently station ground-combat troops on the territory of new
members.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told the Finnish newspaper that the alliance's
commitments of neither deploying troops nor moving its military
infrastructure into the territory of the new members should be
written into the NATO-Russian agreement.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and U.S. President Bill Clinton are due to meet
Wednesday and Thursday here, focusing on the NATO expansion
issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
