<HEADLINE> S. Africa Trys to Calm Arms Row With India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and India have
averted a major diplomatic conflict folowing discloures that the
former has supplied Pakistan -- India's longtime arch foe -- with
missiles, local daily Sunday Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
A series of high-powered diplomatic exchanges between South
Africa and India have taken place since the missile sale was
reported last year in an effort to reduce growing tensions in
diplomatic relations between the two countries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
South African foreign affairs director general Rusty Evans was
quoted as saying that his government had spoken to India about
the missile sale in order to persuade that country that the
projectiles were defensive i nature.
</P>
<P>
Evans said the weapons supplied to Pakistan were air-to-air
missiles, which were incapable of being launched against Indian
ground forces in cross-border strike.
</P>
<P>
We gave them the assurance that we were sensitive to regional
issues and that we did not wish to upset the balance of power,
he said.
</P>
<P>
In December last year, South African deputy president Thabo
Mbeki visited India, concluding a formal defense agreement
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
South African president Nelson Mandela is set to go to India
in late March on a workin visit, during which agreements to
promote bilateral tourism and investment might be signed, local
press reported.
</P>
<P>
Evans confirmed that South Africa had begun supplying weapons
to India, but declined to give details of the projects. Informed
sources said that deals between Pretoria and New Dehli include
the refitting of Indian tanks with a sophisticated South African
turret and cannon.
</P>
<P>
Arms sales to India are believed to have exceeded those to
Pakistan in value with numerous other common or garden arms,
including ammunition and military vehicles, being supplied,
Sunday Times said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
