<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Migrant Workers in South China Economic Zone Decreasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The migrant laborers who poured
into Shenzhen, China's first special economic zone, starting in
the early '80s, have begun to leave the city to look for better
opportunities elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the number of migrant workers in this
economic zone on the edge of Hong Kong dropped to 1.74 million at
the end of 1996 from a high of 2.05 million in 1994, which was fed
by an annual increase of 200,000 over the past 10-odd years.
</P>
<P>
Xin Benlan, deputy director of the municipal labor bureau,
attributed the gradual decline mainly to some migrant workers'
inability to adapt to the city's speedy shift to
technology-intensive business.
</P>
<P>
Higher standards for workers were an inevitable development as
Shenzhen carried out its industrial readjustment and changed its
economic growth, the official said. Skilled and more talented
workers were badly needed during the transition from
labor-intensive enterprises to technology-intensive ones, Xin
explained.
</P>
<P>
The city's high-tech enterprises are said to be adding to their
personnel on a large scale this year, but the overwhelming
majority will be college students.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the drop is that more labor-intensive
enterprises, where most migrant workers are employed, are
themselves moving out of Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen adopted regulations in 1995 that required migrant
workers to pay a 300-yuan annual urban sanitation fee and tried to
impose some order on the disorderly migration process. The labor
bureau also keeps close contact with its counterparts in inland
provinces to try to put a limit on the number of workers. This
also restricts the influx. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Southeast China Farmers Working Elsewhere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Because of the fast-growing
economy and improved agricultural productivity, more farmers in
east China's Fujian Province are looking for jobs in
non-agricultural sectors.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics indicate that some 3.91 million rural
laborers worked in non-agricultural sectors last year, an increase
of 200,000 over the previous year, and the fourth year in a row
that the figure has gone up, according to a local official.
</P>
<P>
In addition to looking for temporary jobs in urban areas,
farmer-workers are increasingly looking for jobs among the growing
number of local ventures or in development zones. Township
enterprises are still the main route for surplus laborers.
Industrial, commercial, food service, construction and transport
fields are the most common areas where farmers get a job.
</P>
</TEXT>
