<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia's Ethnic Women Competing in Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Ethnic minority women in north
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region have found new ways of
making money through self-improvement.
</P>
<P>
Lai Xiao, a Mongolian herdswoman of the Hulun Buir League, won
an award in 1995 from UNESCO for her contributions to agriculture
and animal husbandry, by using a new method of lamb-delivery in
winter. With the new method, her flock of a little more than 100
sheep in 1987 increased dramatically to the present 4,000.
</P>
<P>
Lai Xiao is only one of the 600,000-plus ethnic minority women
in the league who have benefitted from a campaign started by local
women's federations to help poor women become literate and to
learn new techniques for their work.
</P>
<P>
The league was approved by the state in 1988 as an economic
reform trial zone in China's ethnic minority areas. Improving the
quality of women's lives was put high on their list of
goals. Women's federations provide information and technical
services free of charge and hold training classes and give
lectures, and 320,000 women of various ethnic groups have mastered
one or two practical skills, and more than 20,000 women have
obtained agriculture or animal husbandry technician certificates.
</P>
<P>
Wu Xueqing, an Oroqen hunter in the Oroqen Autonomous Banner,
has left poverty far behind by growing edible fungus. More than
100 Oroqen women now have adequate food and clothing because they
followed her example.
</P>
<P>
In the Morin Dawa Daur Autonomous Banner, a Daur woman, Liu
Jinfeng, has become known as the "queen of grain". By using
scientific farming techniques, she sold more than one million
kilograms of grain to the state in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Another Daur, Leng Xueyan, set up a gardening service,
providing saplings, flowers, and flower seeds. Her annual income
is said to be nearly 100,000 yuan now and local people call her
"the girl of flowers".
</P>
<P>
Ethnic minority women also show a strong tendency for
competitiveness in other forms of business. Qu Xiuqin, the
Mongolian manager of the Buir Catering Trade Group Corporation in
the city of Hailar, transformed an enterprise that was suffering
from heavy losses into the best in the sector in the region. In
doing so, she was honoured with the title of state model worker.
</P>
<P>
There are many more female directors and managers like Qu who
are making greater contributions to the economic development of
the ethnic minority areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB Poses Threat to Millions of Africans Every </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Over 1.6 million Africans
develop active tuberculosis (tb) every year and many of them will
die without any help having been available to them, according to
a report by the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
According to the report, at least one-third of the population
in Africa is already infected with tb. Only 10 percnet of these
people would ever become sick as the bacillus can remain dormant
for many years, waiting for illness, undernourishment, or fatigue
to weaken the immune system sufficiently so as to encourage
active disease to arise.
</P>
<P>
Since many tb patients in the region are receiving improper or
inadequate treatment which does not provide a complete cure for
their disease, the patients continue to infect others.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that over the next five years, if nothing is
done, Africa will face 10 million new cases of tb, of which as
many as 3.6 million will die, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tb has become the top 10 causes of hospital and
health center visits and the 3rd leading cause of hospital
admission in Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
According to local press report, over the last 10 years the
number of total cases reported to the country's health
institutions has almost doubled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
