<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Agrees to Send Military, Police Advisers to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
APELDOORN, Netherlands, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union
(EU) agreed today to send military and police advisers to Albania
to help restore order there.
</P>
<P>
Meeting informally in the Het Loo Palace, a 17th century former
royal residence in the Dutch town of Apeldoorn, the EU ministers
also agreed to consider providing protection for this mission if
necessary, but stressed this was not a military operation.
</P>
<P>
"The EU is strongly committed to helping Albania restore
civilian structures and law and order," the ministers said in a
statement after their two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
"External assistance is needed immediately for the restoration
of security in particular in and around Tirana," they said.
</P>
<P>
"Among the member states there was readiness to send an
Advisory Mission in the civilian as well as police and military
fields," they stated, adding that the mission would require a
mandate from the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
It was also agreed that a high-level mission would be sent by
the Dutch EU Presidency to Tirana on Monday, comprising
representatives from Albania's EU neighbors Greece and Italy, the
European Commission and the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
</P>
<P>
The ministers also called on Albania to take responsibility for
rebuilding the country and the society.
</P>
<P>
They said the European Commission was ready to provide
humanitarian assistance "as soon as conditions are sufficiently
secure to assure its delivery."
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed that further steps would be
coordinated with the OSCE as well as the Council of Europe.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, deep split emerged among ministers of the
15-nation bloc regarding whether or not to send troops to Albania
that has been in the grip of unrest since January after the
collapse of pyramid investment schemes in which thousands of
Albanians lost their life savings.
</P>
<P>
The protest turned violent more than two weeks ago as rebels
looted weapons from army depots. Several cities in the southern
part of the country are now controlled by rebels.
</P>
<P>
Tirana itself has also witnessed growing unrest as mobs looted
a warehouse of 650 tons of flour last Thursday and raided security
force depots in search of guns.
</P>
<P>
Albanian President Sali Berisha deployed tanks in front of the
main institutions in the country and called on the EU to provide
military assistance to Tirana to restore order.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Italy, Greece, Denmark and France were in favor
of military intervention of some sort, while Britain, Germany and
Sweden were vehemently opposed to this action.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel on Saturday ruled out any
option of his country sending troops to Albania and warned against
hasty military intervention. "German soldiers will not go into
Albania," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Malcolm Rifkind called it "premature"
to talk about military intervention from outside Albania.
</P>
<P>
Danish Foreign Minister Niels Helveg Petersen, whose country
holds the OSCE presidency, however, endorsed the dispatch of
troops saying a "stabilization force" with a "clear mandate and an
exit strategy" should be sent quickly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak: US Committed to Middle East Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
following his week-long three-nation tour, claimed today that the
United States is committed to its role as a sponsor and partner
in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The different perceptions of Egypt and the U.S. now and then
could not mar our bilateral ties," said Mubarak in his first
public appearance since he returned home Saturday night from his
March 8-15 tour, which has taken him to France, the U.S. and
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Egyptian T.V. program "Good Morning
Egypt," the Egyptian president said the U.S. veto of a
European-sponsored resolution condemning the Israeli decision to
set up 6,500 Jewish homes in East Jerusalem does not mean that
the U.S. is against the right of Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Therefore the veto would have "no impact on the strong ties"
between Egypt and the U.S., he said, adding that though he wished
the U.S. had not used the veto in "an urgent matter unacceptable
by Arabs."
</P>
<P>
On the eve of Mubarak's arrival in Washington, the U.S. vetoed
a U.N. Security Council resolution despite its announced
opposition to Israel's plan of building new settlements in
occupied Arab territories, especially in Jerusalem, which both
the Palestinian National Authority and Israel want to have as the
capital of their states.
</P>
<P>
When asked about his visit to Morocco and his expectation on
rallying Arab and Islamic stands on the peace process, Mubarak
said after the 70-minute talks with King Hassan II of Morocco,
they decided to convene the 15 member-Al Quds (Jerusalem)
Committee in March to examine the latest developments related to
the holy city.
</P>
<P>
The committee, made of Saudi Arabia, Bangladesh, Guinea,
Indonesia, Iran, Niger, Jordan, Lebanon, Morocco, Pakistan,
Senegal, Iraq, Syria, Mauritania and the Palestinian National
Authority, was set up by a summit of the Organization of Islamic
Conference back in 1974 with the aim of preventing the city, holy
to Muslims, Christians and Jews alike from Judaization by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat is expected to brief the
committee on the outcome of his contacts with countries that
backed the Oslo accord at an international conference in Gaza
Saturday. King Hassan II will chair the committee meeting and
explain the results of his contacts to contain the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Inquired about his visit to Paris, which reportedly was an
important leg in all his foreign tours, Mubarak said that he has
a "very good" relationships with French leaders, including
President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
But at the same time, he dismissed the claim that France has
adopted a stance favoring the Arabs while the U.S. is siding with
the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
"The French president is convinced of the justice of our cause
and I cannot say that there is a pro-Arab side or another side
biased to Israel," he added.
</P>
<P>
"All of us favor justice until a fair and lasting peace is
realized. This is the view of Paris and all European states as
well as the U.S.," he said.
</P>
<P>
On his way to Washington, Mubarak stopped in Paris last Friday
for talks with Chirac on Egyptian and French efforts to realize a
comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the tweo countries agreed that there was "a
complete agreement of viewpoints on the peace process, bilateral
relations and international questions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
