<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Put On Alert For Letter Bombs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 16 (Xinhua)-- Zimbabwe's Posts and
Telecommunications Corporation (PTC) has been put on alert for
letter bombs allegedly being sent to American targets throughout
the world including those in Zimbabwe, the Sunday Mail reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The letter bombs are believed to be coming from Egyptian
terrorists but an official at the Egyptian embassy in Harare said
joint efforts by Egyptian and American security agents to trace
the origin of the letters in Cairo were not successful.
</P>
<P>
This was being done by people bent on tarnishing Egypt, he
said. "These people are forging Egyptian stamps and postal marks.
It's very easy to forge these things and make them appear
authentic. Evidence shows that nothing was coming out of Cairo,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He, however, confirmed that the letter bombs were being
targeted at Americans and most of the bombs were sent to New York
and one had exploded at a New York newspaper office injuring two
people who were trying to open or examine the letters.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials within the PTC confirmed to the Sunday Mail
that a warning had been sent out by the Switzerland-based
universal postal union for all postal centres to look out for the
letter bombs. The PTC security department was on alert and all
mail with Egyptian postal marks or stamps was being treated with
extreme caution and subjected to "extensive security testing".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Women Still Marginalised: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior government official
said yesterday Zimbabwe will not develop as long as women are
marginalised and denied access to land and credit to start their
own businesses.
</P>
<P>
While discussing women's role in society, secretary for
National Affairs, Employment Creation and Cooperatives Ministry
Tendai Bare-Machirori said there was need to intensify efforts to
economically empower women and eradicate poverty in the country.
</P>
<P>
She said since women constitute more than half of Zimbabwe's
11 million population, they were an important human resource base
and excluding them from positions of power would retard
development of society.
</P>
<P>
She said her ministry would soon come up with a three-year
project to help women enter politics,
</P>
<P>
The project was aimed at increasing participation of all women
in political life, and particular focus would be on this year's
urban and rural district council elections as well as the general
elections in the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
