<HEADLINE> Foreign Observers Thumbs-up Nigeria's Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Some foreign observers in Nigeria
to monitor its local government elections have described the
election on Saturday as peaceful, democratic and a hitch-free
exercise, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Two of them, Ronald Israel of the Congress of the Racial
Equality and Henry Johnson of the City News, were quoted as
saying that they were satisfied with the arrangement and conduct
of the election in all the pollng stations they visited in Kaduna
metropolis, northern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
They were impressed by the enthusiasm exhibited by voters,
which clearly showed Nigeria was on the path of democracy.
</P>
<P>
Joe Lovice, a member of the Congress for Racial Equality
(CRE), said "as a civil rights organization, we are interested in
the situation in Nigeria and we have keenly been following it."
</P>
<P>
He said his team will not report the CRE but will directly
report to the Congress of the United States government.
</P>
<P>
The results of the local government elections and the faithful
execution of the transition to civil rule program of the Nigerian
government would determine if the American Congress would lift
sanctions against Nigeria, he added.
</P>
<P>
In Ibadan, southwestern Nigeria, an international observer
team of three acting under the aegis of America for Democracy in
Africa, visited some polling centers.
</P>
<P>
Joans Wallace, leader of the team, praised the conduct of the
election, describing it as "very orderly".
</P>
<P>
Wallace, whose team also monitored Nigeria's council election
on zero-party basis early last year, expressed faith in the
Nigerian government's capability in bequeathing enduring
democratic rule to the country.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 38 observers from the United States, who form the
Election Witness Team, arrived in the West African country on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The observers, including journalists, publishers, religious
leaders, political activists and members of non-governmental
organizations, were in various parts of Nigeria to monitor the
election.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election has so far widely described as fair and
peaceful, only with some complaints, especially on shortage of
materials and delayed voting.
</P>
<P>
The result of ballots counting is yet to be known.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics said about 56 million Nigerians were
registered as voters nationwide, which is slightly more than half
of the whole population.
</P>
<P>
It is not known at this moment how many people have actually
voted. The Chairman of the National Electoral Commission of
Nigeria (NECON), Chief Summer Dagogo-Jack has said in Aubja, the
national capital, the commission is impressed by the large
turn-out of the voters.
</P>
<P>
But according to the figure gathered by our reporter at a
polling station on Victoria Island, Lagos, only less than 300 of
the 800 registered voters have voted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
