<HEADLINE> Internet Links Up Astronomers Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A team of Chinese scientists at
the Yunnan Observatory have succeeded in transmitting pictures of
their observation through the Internet to their counterparts in
Beijing, and British, Canadian and American cities.
</P>
<P>
On March 6 and 7, astronomers including Ji Kaifan and Song
Qian at the Yunnan Observatory managed to conduct observations
with their advanced equipment and compress pictures which were
transmitted through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
They sent the pictures to Ye Binxun at the Beijing Observatory,
Chu Yi, a visiting Chinese scholar in Florida in the United
States, Doug Paulson in Utah in the US, Vince Wardhaugh in Toronto,
Canada, and Adrian Jupe in South Ampton, Britain.
</P>
<P>
On receiving the pictures from the Internet, the scientists in
different places held discussions and then made suggestions to the
observers in Yunnan.
</P>
<P>
In two days, scientists at the Kunming Observatory conducted
14 hours of observation with a cost of only 400 yuan (48 US
dollars) for the telecommunication fee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
