<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Head of State Reportedly Avoids Voting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lagos, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's head of state General
Sani Abacha, and the First Lady Maryam, did not vote during
Saturday's local government elections although they have
registered as number one and two voters.
</P>
<P>
The move, according to Sunday Champion today, is possibly to
step-aside notions of officially favoring any political party.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, Chief of the General Staff Lt.-Gen. Oladipo Diya
did not vote either, it said.
</P>
<P>
However, major newspapers in the country carried the
explanations of Col. Mohammed Marwa, the military administrator
of Lagos state, who also declined to vote.
</P>
<P>
"I took the decision (not to vote) to avoid
misrepresentation," Marwa was quoted as saying during his tour on
Saturday to one of 8,000 polling centers in the state.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the time, you discover that when a chief executive
decides to cash his vote, chances are that some speculations will
follow and the public will be misinformed," he said, adding that
he did not want to "run into that kind of problem".
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, key government functionaries,
including state administrators and ministers, may be drawing on
the experience of the past.
</P>
<P>
In 1979, the then head of state General Olusegun Obasanjo and
his deputy Maj.-Gen. Shehu Musa Yar Adua voted in the secret
ballot, midwifing the second republic.
</P>
<P>
But opponents fished out their votes and their choice of party
was leaked to the press. Both leaders were accused of bias in the
unfolding tranistion process.
</P>
<P>
The measure that top government functionaries are barred from
Saturday's election is reported to portray them as neutral
umpires in the transition to civil rule program of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
