<HEADLINE> HK Police Vow to Stop Drug Use at Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong police have vowed to
step up measures to stop the use of drugs on the local dance party
scene despite complaints about a mass search last weekend.
</P>
<P>
District Operations Officer of Central, Chief Inspector Patrick
Hodson, said undercover and uniformed police would closely monitor
what he called "rave-type" parties until drug-trafficking at these
events stops.
</P>
<P>
In an unprecedented move, police raided a party in Central last
weekend and searched all the 150 party-goers, staff and the
premises, according to the English-language newspaper Hong Kong
Standard here today.
</P>
<P>
A warrant was issued days before the party by Western
Magistracy on the basis that past arrests for the possession and
sale of drugs had been made at such events, Hodson said.
</P>
<P>
The raid resulted in two arrests and the seizure of a variety
of suspected drugs, including cocaine, eight Ecstasy tablets, a
cannabis joint, a sealed straw believed to contain heroine and two
syringes with possible traces of heroin, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Although some of the party-goers questioned the operation,
Inspector Hodson was quick to defend it. "Any drugs seized and
arrests made is a success in my mind," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
