<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Confrontation is Doomed to Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- In the first week of the 53rd
session of the U.N. Commission on Human Rights, some developed
countries again pursued political confrontation with developing
countries, just as they did in the previous years.
</P>
<P>
Despite justified calls from developing nations to strengthen
cooperation, delegates from two European countries spared no
efforts to attack developing countries at the session for their
human rights practices, creating a tense atmosphere of
confrontation not expected by the international community.
</P>
<P>
The international community has hoped to promote human rights
through dialogue within the framework of the Commission on Human
Rights, on the basis of equality and mutual respect of sovereignty
and under the United Nations Charter and the Vienna Declaration
and Program of Action.
</P>
<P>
In a message to the session, which began on March 10, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan called for a growing alliance of
efforts all over the world for the realization of basic rights and
fundamental freedoms.
</P>
<P>
Xavier Emmanuelli, French State Secretary for Urgent
Humanitarian Action, in his speech, also stressed the need for
dialogue and consensus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Confrontation is Doomed to Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Non-Aligned Movement and China tabled a draft resolution
entitled "Enhancement of International Cooperation in the Field of
Human Rights," which once again called for cooperation, at the
51st session of the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
But developed countries, pursuing political confrontation, cast
negative votes on the resolution supported by 112 U.N. members,
rejecting the call for consensus by a majority of developing
nations.
</P>
<P>
Following the Cold War, Western powers turned the forum of the
Commission on Human Rights into a place of confrontation between
the North and the South. Posing as human rights judges, they
directly targeted the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
During the commission's previous sessions, they pursued
confrontation and produced numerous draft resolutions against
developing countries, politicizing the human rights issue and
practicing double-standards.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, some Western countries, portraying human
rights "models" and "judges," have made every effort to attack
developing countries with so-called human rights abuses while
turning a blind eye to their own inglorious human rights record.
In fact, they have turned the commission into a "court" where they
put developing countries on trial. This, of course, has met with
strong opposition from more and more developing countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Confrontation is Doomed to Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China, the largest developing country of the world, is one of
their major targets. Over the past six years, there have been six
attempts against China. But all the attempts have failed because
of the strong opposition from a majority of the commission's
members countries.
</P>
<P>
However, a few developed countries have learned no lesson from
their failures.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the commission's current session, the foreign
ministers from the Netherlands and a Nordic country went so far as
to attack China and other developing countries by name.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that different views have emerged inside the
alliance of developed countries on whether to cooperate with
developing countries to promote human rights or to stick to
confrontation, a few developed countries, out of their prejudice
and political need, are still following their road of collision
with developing countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
