<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Opens First AIDS Patients Hospice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- With the opening of the first
hospice for AIDS patients here on Saturday, Hong Kong's AIDS care
workers made more headway.
</P>
<P>
The Tai Po Lookout will initially provide care for five
residential and 10 day-care patients, according to local press
reports.
</P>
<P>
But the Society for AIDS Care hopes to expand the site by next
summer to accommodate a further 16 full-time patients.
</P>
<P>
Demand for the hospice and home care is growing as Hong Kong's
AIDS sufferers increase. New AIDS cases last year soared by 42
percent to bring the total number of sufferers in the city to 228,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The five residential patients are awaiting the completion of
minor renovations so they can move into the building, leased to
the society for one year.
</P>
<P>
The renovation costs totaled 4.5 million HK dollars (about
590,000 U.S. dollars), the reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Confrontation is Doomed to Failure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At a recent press conference, Dutch Foreign Minister Hans Van
Mierlo claimed that the European Union was prepared to table an
anti-China draft resolution. But he also had to admit that no
final decision was made.
</P>
<P>
In their speech, delegates from many developing countries voiced
their opposition to confrontation and the politicizing of
the human rights issue and called for international cooperation on
promoting human rights. They also expressed strong opposition to
attempts by some developed countries to interfere into other
countries' internal affairs by politicizing the human rights issue
and imposing their views on other countries.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jianmin, head of the Chinese delegation, said that China
calls for cooperation and hopes to avoid confrontation. If some
developed countries choose to impose confrontation on us and
continue name calling, we will have no alternative but keep
company.
</P>
<P>
History has proven that attempts by a few developed countries,
which are playing power politics, to impose their human rights
standards and values on the majority of the international
community are doomed to failure. 
</P>
