<HEADLINE> Smoking in Pregnancy Increases Risk of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A latest study in Israel has
shown that the risk of having a mentally handicapped baby is at
least 50 percent higher to pregnant women who smoke than those who
do not.
</P>
<P>
The study, carried in today's Jerusalem Post, noted that the
pregnant women who smoke over a pack of a cigarettes a day are
75 percent more likely to have a mentally deficient child.
</P>
<P>
This is in addition to a much greater risk of low birth
weight, complications during delivery and crib death, said the
study, which was conducted at Ben-Gurion University in southern
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Alon Margalit, staff member of the Family Medicine Department
at the Ben-Gurion University said that he hoped the result of
the study would induce mothers to stop smoking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
