<HEADLINE> Floods Hit Malawi-Mozambique Border Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rains have hit the
Malawi-Mozambique border areas along the Shire river, with 80,000
Malawians and 20,000 Mozambicans displaced, according to a news
dispatch reaching here today from Blantyre, Malawi.
</P>
<P>
These are said to be the worst floods since 1989. "the
situation is serious as we need a lot of assistance because the
people have lost everything," a local official was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the loss of property and livestock, the railway
line in Malawi has been extensively damaged and the government
has launched an appeal for 14 million US dollars to rehabilitate
the railway.
</P>
<P>
The resident representative of the United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) Terence Jones said that the UN recently
contributed 200,000 US dollars towards relief efforts, in
addition to 266,000 dollars donated by Japan and 260,000 dollars
by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
However, the Malawi commissioner for desaster and
preparedness, Lucius Chikuni said that a total of 200 million
Malawi kwacha (13.27 million US dollars) will be required both
for relief and for the rehabilitation of bridges and roads
destroyed by the floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
