<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda, Sudan Talks Fail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Talks to end hostility between
Uganda and Sudan have failed after three days of intensive
discussions, reported the local daily "the New Vision" today.
</P>
<P>
Mediators for the talks from Iran and Malawi were very
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's first deputy prime minister and minister of foreign
affairs Eriya Kategaya, who led the Ugandan delegation was
quoted as saying," for a change today (Saturday), we only issued
a statement instead of a communique as usual because we failed to
come up with what should be a communique."
</P>
<P>
Kategaya who spoke to the paper shortly after the aborted
talks yesterday at the Entebbe airport, 40 km south of here,
attributed their failure to the downgrading of the talks by Sudan
and the kidnapping of children from Uganda to Sudan.
</P>
<P>
He said, all the meetings had been at the head of state level
or full ministers but Sudan has decided to send a civial servant,
a first under secretary in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Sudan was represented by under secretary Ali Elnimari, who
could not commit his country at a higher political level.
</P>
<P>
On kidnapping of children from Uganda to Sudan, he said," 26
girls are still in rebel captivity at a place called Aruu in
Sudan."
</P>
<P>
Sudan never wanted it included in a communique on the talks,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Malawi and Iran had agreed to sign a joint letter regarding
the matter, but Malawi later withdrew because they failed to come
to a consensus on the wording.
</P>
<P>
The talks, held in Entebbe were chaired by the Iranian
minister of foreign affairs Ali Akhbar Velayati. The Malwian
foreign minister Nga Mtafu also attended as a mediator.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was to review and re-assess the situation
regarding the nomalisation of the Uganda-Sudan relations since
the last meeting held in Tehran from November 3-4 last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Kategaya was optimistic that the failure of the talks
does not mean the end of the whole process of searching for
peace. "We still have the door open... if Sudan becomes open, we
shall go by that," he added.
</P>
<P>
Sudan and Uganda have denounced each other for supporting
other country's rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
