<HEADLINE> Ugandan Rebel Leader Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kampala, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Juma Oris, the leader of the
rebel West Nile Bank Front (WNBF), was killed, military sources
confirmed yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader was killed in a battle between his troops and
the government troops earlier yesterday near the Uganda-Sudan
border, "the Monitor" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The WNBF rebels were suffering three major blows recently:
they have lost major camp bases in eastern Zaire in the wake of
the advance of Zairean rebels, their camp bases in southern Sudan
also have fallen in the offensive of Sudanese rebels, they
incurred a major loss in the last few weeks during the operations
launched by the government troops in north-western Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Juma Oris was the former land minister and then was
transferred to be minister of information and finally the foreign
minister under the rein of former dictator Idi Amin. He went to
exile in Sudan after the collapse of Amin's regime in 1979 and
formed the WNBF in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The death of Juma Oris is a notable victory of the government
troops in the north. Yoweri Museveni, the commander-in-chief of
the armed forces and the president of Uganda, put forward a new
strategy to eliminate the rebellion in the north recently.
President Museveni and Mugisha Muntu, the army commander, are
still in the north to oversee army operations there.
</P>
<P>
There are two main rebel groups acting in northern Uganda:
WNBF and the lord's resistance army. The main forces of lra
retreated to southern Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
