<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Depositors' Clear Identities Required </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A local tax expert called for the
establishment of a new deposit system requiring individuals to use
real names when opening savings accounts, according the Business
Weekly of today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The system would help reduce tax evasion and increase state
revenue, the paper quoted an expert as saying.
</P>
<P>
Depositors' identities would be linked with the income tax
information and would enable financial departments to learn
depositors' actual incomes. It would tighten inspection of
personal income tax and help taxation institutions collect taxes,
said Li Bengui, a researcher with State Taxation Administration.
</P>
<P>
Under the existing system, people can open several accounts
without using their real names.
</P>
<P>
The export believed that electronic networks now installed in
all major banks enable the rules to be adopted.
</P>
<P>
Under China's existing tax system, value-added taxes, business
taxes and sales taxes are the main sources of tax revenue, at
least 60 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese tax collectors last year registered 19.3 billion
yuan in income tax, up 46.8 percent from the previous year. The
figure, however, is "far from satisfactory," as the expert put it.
</P>
<P>
Even the tax rate remained low, tax evasion is also rampant, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Insufficient methods for investigating workers' earnings is
believed one of the key reasons for the evasion.
</P>
<P>
Chinese people have deposited more than 3,800 billion yuan in
personal savings accounts last year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe China can collect billions of yuan from taxing
saving's interest, which will substantially contribute to state
revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
