<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Japan Hold Security Consultation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- China and Japan held a frank and
in-depth consultation here Saturday on the security in the
Asia-Pacific region and the implications of the Japanese-U.S.
Security Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yi, head of the Chinese delegation and director of the
Asian Affairs Division of the Foreign Ministry, expressed China's
concern over the fact that Japan and the United States have been
strengthening their military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He urged Japan to act with caution on this issue and refrain
from going against the tide of history.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that Japan will stick to its postwar "defensive only"
policy and continue to pursue peace and development.
</P>
<P>
Kato Ryozo, head of the Japanese delegation and
director-general of the Asian Affairs Division of the Foreign
Ministry, said that in view of historical lessons, Japan will
never seek to become a military power nor will it develop
offensive armaments.
</P>
<P>
He said that Japan will abide by its "defensive only" policy
and play an international role primarily in the economic and
cultural fields.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that there will be no change in the scope of
application as far as the Japanese-U.S. Security Treaty is
concerned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
