<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aid-the-Poor Project in South China Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- With loans from the World Bank
(WB), south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region has made
progress in an aid-the-poor project in its 12 poorest counties.
</P>
<P>
More than 23 percent of the total WB loans, or 266 million
yuan, has been used for the development of education, health care,
agriculture and transportation in the counties.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the poverty-stricken areas have set up more than
90,000 square meters of buildings, and added 27,800 hectares of
crops, 39,000 head of livestock, and 103 kilometers of roads.
</P>
<P>
In addition 43,800 rural surplus laborers have been sent out
for construction in other places, 76,000 people have access to
adequate water supply, and 62,000 students from impoverished
families have opportunities to go to school.
</P>
<P>
The WB loans for the project equal more than 1.1 billion yuan,
and is scheduled to be totally spent by the year of 2001.  
</P>
</TEXT>
