<HEADLINE> Peru Considers Ex-Ecuadoran Minister's Asylum Request </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Peruvian government is
considering whether to grant asylum to Enrique Villon, former
Ecuadoran finance minister under the deposed president Abdala
Bucaram, the local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Enrique Villon entered Peru "illegally" last week, carrying an
official passport "that did not give him permission to leave
(Ecuador) nor to enter (Peru)," Peruvian Interior Minister Cesar
Verduga was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Villon was picked up by Peruvian police on March 8 during a
sweep for illegal immigrants in the northern border town of Aguas
Verdes.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that he would be subject to persecution and
assassination in Ecuador, Villon said he would seek asylum in Peru.
</P>
<P>
However, Verduga said last Sunday that Villon would be returned
to Ecuador on March 10 where he was sought in a wide-ranging
investigation into corruption in the Bucaram administration.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Villon officially requested political asylum from
the Peruvian Foreign Ministry, and was moved on Friday to a
detention center in Lima for "security reason."
</P>
<P>
Bucaram, who fled to Panama, was ousted February 6 on charges
of corruption and incompetence after six months in office.
</P>
<P>
He was accused of stealing 28 million dollars from federal
funds and international loans. A senior legislator has claimed
that Bucaram and some of his closest aides had grabbed nearly 58
million dollars from "special funds."
</P>
<P>
Villon was reportedly carrying some 3.4 million dollars with
him when he entered Peru. 
</P>
