<HEADLINE> Two U.S. Airlines Accused of Tax Evasion in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Two U.S. airlines, Delta
Airlines and United Airlines, have not paid taxes on their incomes
collectively amounting to 80 million rupees (2.25 million U.S.
dollars) in India over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
Directorate of Revenue Intelligence (DRI) sources said here
today that the DRI came across evidence of the alleged tax evasion
while probing the airlines' reported misuse of customs duty
exemptions on baggage screening machines.
</P>
<P>
India's Customs Department granted the former Pan Am Airlines
duty exemption for installing a baggage screening machine at the
Delhi and Mumbai (Bombay) international airports in 1989. The
exemption was granted on condition that it would use the two
machines only for its own passengers.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, Pan Am Airlines was taken over by Delta Airlines and
the former's Delhi route was taken over by the United Airlines in
December 1995.
</P>
<P>
Investigations have revealed that the two U.S. airlines had
allowed passengers of other airlines to use the screening
machines. It was later discovered that the airlines had charged
other airlines a rental fee. No tax, however, was paid to the
Indian authorities on the rental income, the DRI sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
