<HEADLINE> BSE Market Remains Calm This Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- After the budget boom at the
end of February and early March and a big crash in the subsequent
week, this week's Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market activity
remained relatively calm.
</P>
<P>
Although Monday began with a crash of around 101 points, the
market recovered by the end of the day. Tuesday's trading
witnessed a renewed vigor although not many gains could be
sustained. The Sensitive Index finished with a 36-point rise. With
a 13-point jump the next day and a loss of three and nine points
over the two subsequent sessions, trading remained sluggish.
</P>
<P>
The market was through with technical correction and all poised
for yet another rally, market men said.
</P>
<P>
This week's net loss of just about nine points was indicative
of the nervousness slowly vanishing. The Sensitive Index was
steady at 3,745 level. A renewed rally might take the Sensitive
Index to the 3,900-point level, they said.
</P>
<P>
If the political scenario remains stable, there is no cause of
worry, they added.  
</P>
