<HEADLINE> More Than 260 Foreign-funded Firms Operate in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Forty-two foreign-funded
enterprises have been set up in Cuba since the United States
passed the Helms-Burton law in March last year to discourage
foreign investment in the island nation, the local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Of the more than 260 foreign-funded companies in Cuba, 80 were
set up after the country passed the law on foreign investment in
September 1995.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-six were established in 1996, the official daily Granma
reported and 53 percent of the total were funded by member
countries of European Union.
</P>
<P>
Most of the investment came from Spain, Canada, Italy, France,
Mexico, the Netherlands and Britain, which operate about 200 of
such firms.
</P>
<P>
Cuba's first joint venture was established in the tourism
sector nine years ago. So far, there are 30 joint ventures engaged
in oil extraction, 85 in industries, and 45 in tourism.
</P>
<P>
Cuba has signed agreements with 19 countries to promote and
protect investment in the country, and are negotiating 30 similar
agreements with other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
