<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Criticizes Developed Nations for Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Federation of Indian Export
Organizations (FIEO) has criticized developed countries for
various non-tariff barriers against developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The concept of "eco-friendliness" is posing a threat to
products of developing countries and is virtually acting as a
non-tariff barrier, the FIEO said.
</P>
<P>
The developed countries are increasingly resorting to
non-trading barriers to keep a check on their imports and this is
hindering India's efforts to export more, an FIEO official quoted
his Director General R. K. Dhawan as saying here today.
</P>
<P>
Countries in Europe and America manage to raise one issue or
another in the guise of environmental protection (or child labor)
without bothering about the difficulties faced by Third-World
countries. The FIEO has taken up the issue with the Commerce
Ministry and expressed its deep concern about the use of
eco-labeling programs as trade barriers against exports from
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
"A strong written submission should be made to the Committee on
Trade and Environment and the World Trade Organization on the
misuse of the eco-labeling schemes to create barriers to imports
from developing countries," Dhawan said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
