<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Registers $616 Million in Trade Deficit in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Panama had a trade deficit of
616.2 million U.S. dollars in 1996, the Panamanian Comptrollership
said in a communique today.
</P>
<P>
The deficit was caused by a decline in most of the country's
exports, and an increase in imports, according to the document.
</P>
<P>
Panama imported 6.231 billion dollars worth of goods in 1996, a
rise of 6.1 percent from the previous year, against an export of
5.615 billion dollars worth of goods.
</P>
<P>
Banana, one of the country's major export products, accounted
for 31.1 percent of the exports, representing a 4 percent
reduction compared with 1995.
</P>
<P>
Fresh shrimp showed a 10.8 drop because of a delay in the
reproductive cycle of white shrimp, while fish meal and fish oil
exports dropped by 52.7 percent and 63.5 percent respectively,
because of a reduction in the capture of anchovies and herring.
</P>
<P>
Green coffee exports also diminished by 43.4 percent as a
result of dropping prices in the international market.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, oil byproducts, which came third in exports,
witnessed a growth of 33.7 percent, and raw sugar posted a 25.7
percent increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
