<HEADLINE> British Airline Considers Flight to Kathmandu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Britain's leading airline is
considering the possibility of operating passenger flights to
Nepal in the future.
</P>
<P>
General Manager of the British Airways Kevin Steele said the
airline would extend its current London-Delhi route to Kathmandu
if it could overcome technical aspects, obtain India's permission
and guarantee a profit, the official daily paper the Rising Nepal
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The British Airways, which is holding its South Asia regional
management meeting here over the weekend, has been conducting a
process of evaluating possible operations in Kathmandu since last
August, Steele said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Kathmandu, the capital city of Nepal, is a
destination with commercial potential as the government here has
launched the Visit Nepal Year 1998 program aimed at attracting
foreign tourists and the German airline Lufthansa stopped its
Kathmandu flights this year due to poor financial performance.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government has already allowed the British Airways
to operate passenger flights between Kathmandu and Delhi, and the
airline now needs permission from the Indian authorities, the
general manager said.
</P>
<P>
The British Airways' next round of talks with the Indian
government on the issue of traffic rights between Kathmandu and
Delhi will be held in May this year, he added.  
</P>
