<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French President Hails Bolivia's Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LA PAZ, March 15 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques
Chirac today hailed the reforms being implemented in Bolivia,
saying that "France is on the side" of that South American country.
</P>
<P>
"Bolivia has taken the right road and France is on its side,"
Chirac said in a speech at the Bolivian parliament building.
</P>
<P>
He said the reforms in Bolivia encourage France to support
Bolivia in the European Union, in the Group of Seven, and in the
multilateral institutions.
</P>
<P>
The South American country, which has transformed its political
system and started justice reforms, has opened itself and has
achieved spectacular changes, said the French president.
</P>
<P>
Chirac arrived in Bolivia Friday after a visit to Uruguay as
part of an eight-day tour of five South American countries.
</P>
<P>
He said Bolivia is fully qualified to be close to the Southern
Common Market (Mercosur), which groups Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay
and Paraguay, at a time when the European Union (EU) and Mercosur
have started to diversify and reinforce their links.
</P>
<P>
The EU and Mercosur signed a landmark cooperation agreement in
December 1995 designed to pave the way for a trans-Atlantic free
trade accord. Chile and Bolivia have signed on as associates of
the regional trade bloc.
</P>
<P>
The French president stressed the importance of combating drugs
as an absolute priority for the Bolivian government.
</P>
<P>
He said he has proposed to the European Union Commission that
the system of custom tariff exemptions be extended to products
that will substitute drug-producing plants and that Europe give
special assistance to Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
The European Union and Mercosur have agreed to try to reach a
free trade accord in two stages ending in 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
