<DOCNO> XIE19970316.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reform Debt Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The State Administration of
Foreign Exchange (SAFE) is considering setting different ceilings
for outstanding foreign debts of designated foreign exchange banks
and non-banking financial institutions with foreign borrowing
rights, according to today's Business Weekly of China Daily.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the financial institutions will be able
to make their own decisions in adjusting their debt structure as
long as they keep their long and medium-term foreign debts within
the ceiling and meet the central's bank's required
assets-liabilities ratio.
</P>
<P>
The reform is aimed at helping financial institutions reduce
debt risks and use foreign funds more efficiently, it quoted a
SAFE official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The official said most financial institutions seemed to welcome
the reform. The administration is expected to finish drafting a
reform plan this year but the implementation date can't be set
until the State Council approves the plan.
</P>
<P>
The long and medium-term foreign debts refer to foreign loans,
leasing and overseas bonds with at least one-year terms.
</P>
<P>
The state is adopting project management systems for those
kinds of debts. The State Planning Commission sets foreign debt
quotas for large construction projects that rely on financial
institutions for foreign funds.
</P>
<P>
Under the existing system, the financial institutions fail to
select the best interest rate and term for foreign borrowing
according to market changes, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Since the foreign debt quotas are valid within certain periods,
financial institutions sometimes have to borrow money to avoid
wasting quotas although market conditions aren't favorable.
</P>
<P>
"Our foreign debt management should go to the market and give
some autonomy to financial institutions," the official said.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the State Council, or China's cabinet, started the
reform experiment in 1992 by giving autonomy to China
International Trust and Investment Corporation (CITIC).
</P>
<P>
CITIC was empowered to borrow overseas without prior approval
as long as its outstanding foreign debt was kept below the ceiling
during the Eighth Five-Year Plan (1991-1995). Its foreign debt
dropped from 2.5 billion US dollars in 1992 to last year's 2.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
The government last year extended CITIC's autonomy another five
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
