<HEADLINE> OSCE Considers Military Intervention in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The permanent council of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) met
here today to discuss solutions to the crisis in Albania.
</P>
<P>
The OSCE proposed to send troops to Albania to help restore
public order in that country, the Austrian news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
It also proposed international organizations provide financial
aid for Albania, promising that the OSCE would help it establish
democratic mechanism.
</P>
<P>
The European organization has sent a special envoy, Franz
Vranitzky, twice to Albania for mediation. Vranitzky was former
Austrian chancellor.
</P>
<P>
After talks with Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim Fino and the
rebel representatives respectively Friday, Vranitzky said that
both sides have agreed to an international military and police
intervention to help restore order in the strife-ridden country.
</P>
<P>
European Union (EU) foreign ministers have been holding
different views on sending troops to Albania and they are expected
to meet Saturday and Sunday in the Netherlands to discuss the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel stressed that
measures must be adopted to prevent the situation in Albania from
further worsening, saying that his country would provide food aid
for Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
