<HEADLINE> Chinese Renminbi Slightly Devalues Last Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The renminbi yuan closed down at
8.2955 against the US dollar on February 28, slightly down
compared with 8.2925 on February 3, the month's first trading day,
according to today's Business Weekly of China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The yuan was bullish before the Chinese Lunar New Year that
fell on February 7, scoring a 20-month high closing price of
8.2918 against the US dollar a day before the festival.
</P>
<P>
A Bank of China dealer attributed the rise to a huge demand
for the renminbi as the festival approached, and reduced
intervention from the People's Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
But the yuan fell to 8.295 against the US dollar on February
12, the first trading day after the festival holidays.
</P>
<P>
Despite the small devaluation last month, analysts said the
yuan would remain stable thanks to China's sufficient foreign
exchange reserves, and a strong foreign trade performance with
rising exports and the declining inflation.  enditem

