<HEADLINE> Austrian Company to Run Garment Factory in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 16 (Xinhua) -- An Austrian company will operate a
women's garment factory in Myanmar, leasing land from the
Cooperatives Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Under the land lease agreement reached here on Saturday between
 Anita Asia Ltd. of Austria and the Cottage Industries Department
of the Myanmar Ministry of Cooperatives, the Austrian company will
build the factory with 1 million U.S. dollars, the official paper
The New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
The factory, which will be fully owned by the Austrian side,
will be built in eight months and it will produce brassieres and
pants for export, it said.
</P>
<P>
The factory is believed to be the second Austrian project in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The latest official statistics show that foreign investment in
the country's manufacturing sector ranks second after oil and gas
with 1.09 billion U.S. dollars in 76 approved projects out of a
total foreign investment of 5.38 billion dollars from 21 countries
and regions.
</P>
<P>
Companies from Singapore, Britain, Japan, Hong Kong, Thailand,
South Korea, Indonesia and China have invested in this sector by
mostly forming joint ventures with Myanmar's state-owned
enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
