<HEADLINE> Central China Increases Efforts to Combat Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province
brought 1,677 corruption cases to the court last year, in which
1,398 people were involved, according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that provincial anti-corruption
departments have increased efforts at fighting corruption, with
2,815 cases of economic crimes investigated last year, and more
than 1.9 billion yuan (almost 230 million US dollars) was
recovered for the state.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 enterprises were investigated last year, and more
than 700 economic crimes discovered in the process.
</P>
<P>
The province has established 104 offices with 147 officials
whose specific job is overseeing work in some major industries and
departments.
</P>
<P>
"These officials help enterprises investigate economic crimes
and improve management, and in the process helping their
business," said an official with the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
The Yue Yang Chemical Factory was recovering from losses
finally five months after four people were found guilty of
embezzlement and improvements were made with the help of
anti-corruption officials.
</P>
<P>
"We have had an average monthly increase of two million yuan in
output value since then," said the head of the factory, explaining
that his plant is now in fairly good shape.  
</P>
</TEXT>
