<HEADLINE> Bosnian Muslims Angered By Serb Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A Bonsian Muslim leader on
Saturday criticized the Serb authorities for their decision to
forge closer military and economic ties with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Harris Silajdzic, the co-prime minister of the Bosnian central
government, told the Bih TV that the Serb authorities' move would
threaten the peace process in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the Republika Srpska (RS) parliament, with 61
votes for and 11 against, approved the agreement signed last month
between Serb and Yugoslav leaders on strengthening their military
and economic ties.
</P>
<P>
Silajdzic said the Muslim side would address the issue to the
U.N. security Council and the Contact Group which consists of four
Western powers and Russia.
</P>
<P>
"Not only the implementation of the Dayton agreement is now in
question, but the peace too," Silajdzic said.
</P>
<P>
Silajdzic and other Muslim leaders have argued that RS has no
authority to sign such an agreement with a foreign country since
it is only one of the two entities of Bosnia. 
</P>
