<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet's Efforts in Building Infrastructures Pay Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- With financial and technological
assistance from the central government and other parts of the
country, southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region has made
remarkable achievements in its infrastructure buildup.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the 1990s, the state has invested some
13.1 billion yuan in the fixed assets of Tibet, with 11.43 billion
yuan earmarked for the infrastructure. In 1997, over 2.9 billion
yuan will go to the sector.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the region's electricity-generating capacity stands
at 200,000 kw, with a yearly generation of 545 million kwh,
according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Tibet has rebuilt its highway that connects
with Nepal, and repaired all bridges on the Chinese section of the
international road. Meanwhile, new technology has been adopted to
improve the Qinghai-Tibet and Sichuan-Tibet highways so as to
reduce the losses caused by natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The efforts to develop the telecommunications sector have been
successful, as all Tibetan counties have installed programmable
telephones and 97 percent of the counties have entered the
national automatic long-distance telephone switching networks.
</P>
<P>
A 900 mw cellular phone network has been put into operation,
while paging systems have been opened in six prefectures and
cities.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, a large number of water conservancy
projects, including reservoirs and other facilities for irrigation
and electricity generation, have been built in the region, which
have contributed much to the large increase in local agricultural
production.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, central government departments and other
provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities have assisted
Tibet in constructing 62 projects, with a total investment of 3.7
billion yuan. So far, 56 of the 62 projects have been completed.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has also launched its own key projects in the mining
industry involving gold, iron and coal.
</P>
<P>
The region stepped up its efforts last year to introduce more
funds from other places of the country, especially the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
As a major beneficiary of the Glory Program, a nationwide
activity initiated by private businessmen in the country to help
poor areas, Tibet has reached agreements with Glory participants
for 53 projects involving a total investment amounting to 600
million yuan. 26 Glory projects are now under construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
