<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Booming Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's Gross Domestic
Product for the first two months of 1997 surpassed 43 billion
yuan, rising 12.3 percent over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In January and February, the city generated 72.6 billion yuan
in industrial output value, up 12.8 percent over the same period
in 1996, and the sales-production ratio rose nearly three
percentage points to reach 97 percent, according to the Shanghai
Municipal Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The city conducted more than two billion US dollars of exports
during the two months, up more than 10 percent from the figure a
year ago. The East China Export Commodity Fair scheduled this
month in Shanghai is expected to increase exports.
</P>
<P>
Local retail sales of consumer goods hit a record of nearly
22.9 billion yuan during the two months, a 16.5 percent of rise
from the same period of the previous year, while the price growth
rate fell 6.4 percentage points to 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
This year the Shanghai Municipal Government will further
restructure its industrial setup, deepen reforms of local state
enterprises, and open wider to the outside world, hoping to
achieve a 10 percent rise in GDP, 10 percent rise in exports, and
13 percent rise in revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
