<HEADLINE> North China's Animal Husbandry Becoming Leading Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Animal husbandry in north
China's Hebei Province is contributing more to agricultural
development and farmers' pockets, and had an output value of 23
billion yuan last year, accounting for 35 percent of the total
agricultural output.
</P>
<P>
Animal husbandry is no longer a cottage industry but an
independent one and a driving force in developing the rural
economy and in improving the province's industrial structure
adjustment.
</P>
<P>
In some places, farmers are relying more heavily on animal
husbandry for profits. In Dachang county, one third of the
farmers' income comes from animal husbandry, making the county
fourth in the province in per capita income.
</P>
<P>
The province produced 3.4 million tons of meat last year,
making it fifth in the country, as well as 2.5 million tons of
eggs and 450,000 tons of fresh milk, second and fourth of all the
provinces, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Farmers have changed their traditional methods of raising pigs
for meat and chickens for the Spring Festival, and 1,100 animal
breeding villages, involving 600,000 specialized households, have
appeared.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 percent of the farmers in Dachang county are
engaged in activities related to breeding, processing, and
marketing of animals. The county's output value from cattle and
sheep last year exceeded 300 million yuan, making it a major
source of local revenue.
</P>
<P>
The province has set up over 90 livestock product bases that
support 50 leading enterprises. The Sanlu Dairy Company has a more
than 20 percent share of China's dairy products market, and has 59
dairy farms and 1,200 households with milk cows as suppliers.
enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
