<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Renew Old Houses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital city will
spend more than 20 billion yuan on urban renewal, changing the
face of Beijing by the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The city will pull down more than five million square meters of
condemned houses and relocate 120,000 to 150,000 households in the
next four years.
</P>
<P>
Beijing intends to raise per capita living space for local
urban residents from the present 13.2 square meters to 15 square
meters by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Former residents are encouraged to live in the suburbs while
construction takes place.
</P>
<P>
Beijing began full-scale urban renewal since 1990, and had
already transformed more than four million square meters of
condemned houses by 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
