<HEADLINE> Wuhan to Open Wider to Outside World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Wuhan, capital of central China's
Hubei Province, plans to open wider to the outside world and
accelerate the development of its export-oriented economy this
year, Mayor Wang Shouhai said.
</P>
<P>
The city will focus on improving the investment environment and
attracting investments from both home and overseas, Wang said,
adding that funding from both consortia or small firms is welcome,
as are capital- and technology-intensive projects.
</P>
<P>
This year, the city aims to use 930 million US dollars of
foreign investment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wuhan has adopted a series of measures in recent years to
improve its investment environment. In 1996, the city passed a
regulation governing the collection of fees from foreign-backed
companies. Fee rates were publicized and unnecessary fees were
eliminated. Complaint centers for foreign businessmen also were
set up.
</P>
<P>
"The regulations were welcomed by foreign investors," the mayor
said.
</P>
<P>
Wuhan has also taken a step forward in infrastructure
construction: work on the Yangtze Baishazhou Bridge will soon
start, and an environmental project to deal with pollution, funded
by World Bank in loans, has been launched. Repair of the Zhongnan
highway and the expansion of a waterworks have been completed.
</P>
<P>
Development of posts and telecommunications has progressed,
Wang said. The Tianhe Postal Transit Center has opened and will
provide local telephone service to one million people.
</P>
<P>
Wuhan, located along the mid-stream of the Yangtze River, will
also speed up the building of five-star hotels and take steps to
open the Tianhe Airport to international flights.
</P>
<P>
Wang went on to say that the city will push the reforms of
foreign trade firms, increase technological trade and service
trade, and adopt an export agent system, so that earnings from
exports can increase 11.9 percent to reach 900 million US
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
