<HEADLINE> Primakov, Albright hold talks for Helsinki Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov and U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
held talks on Saturday for preparation of Helsinki summit between
Soviet President Boris Yeltsin and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to having a good meeting," Albright
said as she welcomed Primakov to her office. The Russian foreign
minister arrived in Washington this afternoon and then detoured to
the Russian embassy before meeting with Albright.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of Primakov's talks in Washington with U.S.
leaders, including Defense Secretary Williams Cohen on Sunday and
President Bill Clinton on Monday, is to try to find guidelines for
a new round of U.S. and Russian arms control and to narrow
differences on NATO enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and his government has been opposed to NATO's plan to
invite former member states of the Warsaw Pact when NATO hold a
summit in Madrid in July and to deployment of conventional weapons
to the territory of Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin registered his objections again on Friday to the NATO
enlargement, saying, "What the Americans are proposing -- moving
conventional weapons to the territory of Eastern Europe -- would
amount to a 'cordon sanitaire'. We won't go along with that."
</P>
<P>
But the United States ruled out any limits on the NATO
enlargement or the weapons that new members could bring into the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
While the United States has offered several concessions to
counter Russia's objections to NATO enlargement, it would not
negotiate limits on the new members.
</P>
<P>
the United States, trying to placate Russia, has proposed a
charter, defining Russia's ties with the Western alliance,
including granting Russia full membership in the G-7 Group
</P>
<P>
Another issue on the agenda during Primakov's talks with U.S.
leaders is to produce guidelines for reducing their nuclear
weapons arsenals beyond the sharp cut provided by the 1993 START
II treaty.
</P>
<P>
The Russian parliament is baling at ratifying the START II
treaty as it would strip Russia of its most potent long-range
warheads and the Russian economy cannot afford to build-up
single-warhead missiles.
</P>
<P>
Since there is no progress made on the issue of START II on the
side of Russia, there is no movement on proposed follow-on START
III reductions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
