<HEADLINE> Von Gruenigen Wins World Cup Giant Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Michael von Gruenigen of
Switzerland and Italy's Deborah Compagnoni extended their
season-long dominance of the event while Kjetil Andre Aamodt saw
his chances for the overall title virtually vanish at the World
Cup Finals at Vail, Colorado, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Von Gruenigen and Compagnoni won their giant-slalom races in
the World Cup Finals, each coming from second place to overtake
the first-run leader.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old von Gruenigen, who also won the world
championship title this year, was second by 0.18 of a second after
the first run, finished with a combined time of two minutes, 18.58
seconds.
</P>
<P>
Salzgeber was second in 2:19.57, with compatriot Andreas
Schifferer, winner of Thursday's super-giant slalom race, taking
third place in 2:19.97.
</P>
<P>
Compagnoni, who earlier clinched the season giant-slalom title
and won the event in the World Championship, posted her fourth
straight victory in seven giant slalom races this season.
</P>
<P>
Compagnoni, 0.17 seconds behind first-run leader Katja
Seizinger, overtook Seizinger with a second run that was 0.55
seconds quicker than the German's. She finished with a combined
time of 2:11.45.
</P>
<P>
Aamodt, second best in the giant slalom standings, earned 36
points for his finish, a result that probably scuttled his chances
of overtaking France's Luc Alphand for the overall title.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian, who won the World Cup title in 1994, now trails
Alphand by 70 points with only Sunday's slalom remaining to the
season.
</P>
<P>
Aamodt, who ranks only eighth in the slalom standings, needs to
win or finish second on Sunday to pass Alphand, who is poised to
become the first Frenchman since Jean-Claude Killy in 1968 to win
the overall crown.
</P>
<P>
Aamodt's best slalom finish this season was third in the
season-opening slalom in Park City. In his last three slaloms, the
Norwegian has finished 10th, 11th and 15th. 
</P>
</TEXT>
