<HEADLINE> North China Replaces South as Grain-Supplying Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- China's decades-long system of
transporting grain from the southern part of the country to the
north has undergone a fundamental change, according to a report by
the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the crop-growing capability in north China has
increased, while in south China, especially the coastal areas in
the southeast, it has decreased. To maintain the national balance
of grain supplies, large quantities of grain produced in the north
have been transported from there southward.
</P>
<P>
From 1983 to 1995, China's year-on-year increase of grain
output totalled 79.34 million tons. Of the total, north China made
up 70 percent, while the south accounted for 30 percent,
Shanghai-based Xinmin Evening News reported.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River Delta and Pearl River Delta have taken the
lead in shifting from grain exporting to importing.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, 10 of the 16 southern China provinces and regions were
short of grain, with the shortfall amounting to 25 million tons.
</P>
</TEXT>
