<HEADLINE> EU to Offer Big Money to Help Angola's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will
provide 167 million European Currency Units (ECU) in 1997, up 45
percent over 1996, to help Angola undertake post-war
socio-economic reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Gaspar Cardoso, a senior official in the Angolan Ministry for
Planning, said today that a related accord will be signed when
the Angolan government and the EU finish their current
negotiations on the details of how to use the money.
</P>
<P>
The EU money will be mainly used in repairing war-damaged
roads and reconstructing and developing cities in the
southern African country, said Cardoso.
</P>
<P>
The EU assistance aims at facilitating Angola's economic
reforms, increasing domestic production, developing the private
sector and creating job opportunities, he added.
</P>
<P>
The EU has offered about 580 million ECU to Angola since it
opened an office in the country in 1986. Among the money 82
million were used in developing projects and 78 million in
restoring infrastructures, he added. enditem

